    'topic' => ' Traveller economics',
    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> Our party is about to enter the Sword Worlds cluster in our search
> for fame and profit. As a result, I\'ve got a couple of questions for
> the more economically minded members of the list.

> How hard is it to use Imperial credits, OUTSIDE the Imperium?

Depends on the local government. *And* on how much *trade* with the
Imperium the world has.

> The Sword Worlders (and for that matter the Darrians) have their own
> currency, right?

Probably.

> I assume that they conduct trade with the Imperium, so there must be
> some way to exchange currencies.

Simplest way of all. You buy a cargo at one end with Imperial Credits
and sell it at the other end for local money. The *average* of such
transactions is the "real" exchange rate. 

Note that this means that given the right circumstances, the A->B rate
may not be the inverse of the B->A rate. 

In actual practice, governments (or banks) at each end set their own
rates based on a combo of their "best guess" at the real rate, and
their desire to make a profit. They may also want to affect the rate
for reasons of their own.

> Is the money traded like it is on our <rl> stock markets?
> Who sets the exchange rates? That is; how do they decide that a Swordworlder
> buck is worth half a credit or whatever?

See above. In the real markets, exchange rates are of two kinds
"official" rates, which are what a givernment will pay in exchange for
its own currency, and "market" rates which are what the *other* traders
in the market will pay. 

> Is it due to market forces, and does that mean that players would be able to
> dabble on the money market?

A combo of market forces, "chaos" (in the mathematical sense) and
governments and other large players trying to "force" values to where
they want them.

> Finally, how is the money backed? Do they use something like the gold
> standard (ie the money is issued against gold and precious metal
> reserves held by the government), or what?

Monies "backed" by something tend to run into problems when the supply
of "something" expands to fast (New World gold *ruined* the Spanish
economy). They also run into problems when the supply is too *small*
(basicly, the supply of "cash" is insufficient to allow for all the
transactions required). 

You see, "money" is an *abstraction*. A means of trying to keep score.
Basicly, money is merely a fancy system of "IOUs" that functions
because people expect it to function.

A "dollar" has *no* intrinsic value. Its worth depends on what goods or
services people are willing to give you in exchange for it. And that
changes depending on location and circumstances. 

Currency gets *really* messy. The Russian Ruble before the collapse of
the USSR is a good example. They had something like *four* "rubles"
which *in theory* were of equal value. 

There was a gold-backed ruble used *only* for foreign exchange. That
is, for buying things from outside. Possesion of them *inside* the
USSR, much less trying to convert them to gold was a crime!

There was an *internal* ruble. The stuff they paid people in and that
the average person had to pay for things with. These were illegal to
take out of the country. It was even difficult to buy good for export
with them!

When American companies like Pepsi started selling in the USSR, they
had some *real* problems getting their profits out. Pepsi finally
worked out a deal where for every liter of Pepsi sold in the USSR, they
could export a liter of Stoli vodka! Pepsi wasn\'t exactly upset at the
deal... 

I think the third kind of rubles were used by the folks with "special
priveleges" and were only usable in shops catering to such. With
*these* rubles, you could buy imported goods. Having them was
"supposed" to be limited to certain people, but in practice, if you had
some, you could use them. 

I forget what the fourth type was.

Admittedly, this is an extreme value, but *because* it is so extreme, I
think it helps get across the idea that the only value a currency has
lies in what you can buy with it. And that this varies according to
*where* you are. 

Russian internal rubles, even if you could get them out of the country
were utterly *worthless* in the west. But when tourists or other
vistors *entered* the USSR they were *required* to convert their
currency into the internal ruble at an exchange rate very favorable to
the government. 

