    'ts-index' => '1999-10-29.ec497',
    'body' => 'I need some mathematical advice. Sorry to clog bandwidth. Please respond to
the off-topic part offlist.

The Ontario government has come up with a new grading system for school
students. It is roughly as follows:

level 4 - exceeds expectations (>90%)
level 3 - meets expectation (75-90%)
level 2 - meets many expectation, but not all (60-75%)
level 1 - meets bare minimum of expectations (50-60%)

There is also a phantom "level 0", which is a failing grade.  The
government expects level 4 to be rare, no more than 5% of the students;
only time will tell if they stick to their guns when parents arrive (with
lawyers) to argue for marks...

Anyway, my problem is that the government has provided no system for
combining marks from many evaluations into a final grade. Our instructions
are merely to use the "predominant" level, which is pretty vague and not
what we were promised. The new automated gradebook, which was supposed to
do this automatically, has been delayed again, and we have to provide marks
by November 15.

Can anyone provide me with a mathematically valid way of combining these
marks together? Mere averaging doesn\'t work, obviously. The percentage
equivalents I\'ve provided are just guidelines - the actual marks are
arrived at by consulting descriptions of what that level of work should be
like. I\'ll provide more details via private email on request.

Professional note: if we use your idea, I\'ll make certain that you get
co-author status on our report.


ObTrav: There\'s got to be the seeds of a good adventure here. Something
with an impersonal bureaucracy, of course.  I\'ll post something later this
weekend. Promise.
