    'body' => 'On 10/28/99 at 06:20 PM,  "Hughes, Michael" <Michael.Hughes@cbr.defence.gov.au> said:

>HOBBY & TRIVIA SKILLS

>Tired of drab colourless PC & NPCs? Are they simply looking like a
>collection of UPP\'s and same\'o same\'o skills?

>Then spice them on up with hobby or trivia skills. Skills that
>ordinarily don\'t have a place in a game and have no real influence on
>almost any task, but nonetheless could or can be used at some point.
>Chess, fishing, knowledge of Horror TriD or Contemporary Romance
>Fiction could all be yours . . . .

>Give the NPC or PC a number of hobby/trivia skill levels equal to
>his/her Education and let them go nuts. If ever called onto to
>perform a hobby/trivia task, roll Vs an appropriate stat+skill level
>(if unskilled subtract 3) e.g. ice skating or wood-carving then use
>Dex, recalling a specific sport statistic then use Educ.

Excellent idea!  

But EDU might not be the best way to rate certain kinds of hobby
skills.  DEX (or AGL depending on your system) might be better for
skills that depend on physical characteristics and EDU for mental
based skills.  Would levels equal to both DEX and EDU for
appropriate hobby skills be too much?  Also, shouldn\'t the number of
terms the character has "served" be a limit on such skills.

Maybe something like this:  The PC gets 4 levels per term for
hobby/trivia skills.  The maximum limit in levels for physical based
skills is the PC\'s DEX and for mentally based skills is EDU.  The
skills chosen shouldn\'t be profession or career related, and, as
always, the GM has final approval.

This would be great!  Suz\'s character, Mira, can now have that high
skill in Spherical Handball, Cory his cello and musical composition
skills, Martan has a way to be skilled at rock climbing, Woof can
have his archaeology hobby and it doesn\'t affect their professional
and career based skills.


