I\'ve used povray, and it\'s very easy to use, but at least back when I use it
the problem was that it\'s _just_ a renderer .

It doesn\'t really provide you with any tools for interactively designing
anything, you describe all the points, the textures, and the lighting in a
_text_ file, and then tell povray  to render it.

Really easy to use for spheres & squares, etc, but very hard to define
complex 3D objects,  though some people have done some amazing work with it.
If you have some too that can provide you with a three-dimensional point
map, then PovRay can render it.

There are other options out there.  Bryce is nowhere near as expensive as
Light Wave and it has a much better and easier to use interface than
LightWave, though obvioulsy it\'s not as powerful.

Bryce also let\'s you do complete scenes nicely, as it includes Vista-Pro
type landscape tools as well as cloud maps, and specific lighting tools for
replicating the effect of a light source through cloud /haze/fog

Frankie
