I don\'t think that\'s it, either.  I believe in the Second Amendment, I think
that in America, it\'s necessary.  The type of government oppression that it
was designed to forestall would be resisted differently in Japan-- and in
Japan, you don\'t have people living so far away from one another that by the
time the police arrive, the females in the house have been raped, the
valuables taken, and possibly the males have been killed.  There are still
fairly big stretches of America, growing with rural depopulation and the
rise of factory farming, where this is the case.

>>Yeah, well the Japanese don\'t eat cheese. So statistically, you could
argue that we should give up cheese!
>>
>Correlation is not causation and all that.
>
The Japanese didn\'t eat cheese fifty years ago.  The Japanese eat cheese
whenever they feel like it, now.  I\'ve been to Japan, I\'m rather familiar
with the place, McDonalds puts cheese on the burgers there, too.  The
Japanese eat everything that Americans eat, unless they personally dislike a
certain food or have allergies/intolerances, plus everything that they have
always eaten.  Americans are the only people in the world who are really
finicky about funny looking food; we go to other countries and eat our own
food, as a general rule, and unless you live in a really large city, the
food in American "ethnic" restaurants is usually substantially different
from what you\'d get in the country of origin.

I don\'t recall if I ate cheese or not the last time that I was in Japan, but
I\'m pretty sure that I did, because my favorite breakfast to eat over there
consists of the Japanese version of British tea sandwiches and a large glass
of iced tea with sugar syrup in it.  (Yeah, I ate that every day at Comic
Market...)

>Kiri can correct me if I\'m wrong, but my Japanese friends tell me that
Japan has a much higher level of social control than America.
>
It depends upon what you consider annoying.  Hiroshi prefers the United
States but that has a lot to do with the nature of his ambitions and the
fact that he wasn\'t real happy growing up (I wouldn\'t go back to my home
town on a bet, either.)  Many Japanese don\'t want to go back to Japan
because they think that it is too much trouble to keep up the outward
appearances that are expected over there.  I rather like that sort of thing,
and appreciate the fact that you can be as strange, kinky, and weird as you
want to be so long as you have your trash can in the right place and don\'t
force other people to participate in your weirdness as observers.

> Leave your trash can out of place on the curb and the "trash lady" comes
to warn you.  Keep doing it and the neighbourhood reacts. This factor should
be taken into account.
>
What, you like it that people leave their trash cans all over the place, no
matter what everyone else does?  <g>

I think there\'s a high level of social control in AMERICA.  Total strangers
will come up to you and tell you that you shouldn\'t smoke, you\'re too fat to
eat this or that, God help you if you\'re pregnant and you dare to eat
anything in public because someone will have an opinion about it...
Complete outsiders will comment on your clothing, break into your quiet
conversation about a relationship problem to tell you to "Dump the
bastard!", or dump all their problems on you.

People walk right up to you and ask you to change your religion, and they\'re
not respectful about it either.  I\'ve been asked really rude questions by
people I had never seen before about pentacles, prayer beads, etc.  People
stand outside of clinics and shout at you about medical procedures they
disapprove of.

And yet... you can leave your trash can right out in the damn street where
someone could trip over it and break their neck, and no one cares.

The Japanese will pretend not to notice any behavior that isn\'t obtrusive
enough to upset people.  It\'s a skill learned from living in close quarters
for thousands of years.  They may go home and laugh about you to all of
their friends, but you won\'t know about it.

I\'d much rather have people tell me that I need to keep my trash can in the
appropriate place (and keep theirs in the appropriate place) than have
people giving me crap about who comes into and out of my apartment and how
late they stay, or telling me ON THE STREET that I\'m too big to eat this or
that, or giving me unsolicited advice about my personal life, or regaling
everyone on public transit with the details of their drug habit/sexual
affairs/etc., or shoving tracts in my face and inquiring after my soul,
which is probably the most personal thing I can think of....

See, it\'s all how you look at it...  It was very refreshing, on New Years
Morning when we all went to the shrines to get right with the kami, say hi
to Buddha, and make our New Year\'s resolutions to ourselves and our
ancestors, to see that everyone thought the small group of Americans (and a
very few Japanese) who were standing outside the shrines yelling at us that
we needed to change our religion were all nuts, and that they had to stay so
far away from the doors and couldn\'t get up in our faces.

In general, when I\'ve been in Japan, I have felt that total strangers were
much less likely to try and interfere with my behavior than they are here in
America.  If you do something obnoxious in public over there, people just
pretend you don\'t exist.  I think that\'s a more effective way to get people
to change what they do than giving them crap.

Kiri
