> With the Alderson Drive most stars only had connections to a few
> other stars, and many stars weren\'t connected at all.  Might explain
> why the universe appears so flat.

The "physics" of Alderson Dives were worked out in detail by Dan Alderson
from CalTech to Jerry\'s requirements , as well as how to locate Alderson
points, and this was all explained in one of Jerry\'s articles in Galaxy,
"Building the Mote In God\'s Eye" which was later republished in the
collection "A Step Further Out", which in itself is a wonderful quick
reference for all sorts of Travelleresque stuff.

I could reproduce some of the details here if anyone is interested.

For instance, there\'s an article all about how getting out of the gravuity
well of Earth is "Halfway to Anywhere", and another on why "Those pesky
Belters and their Torch Ships" won\'t happen, and one on "Living in the
Asteroids" with all the figures for delta-V betwen planets and time taken at
various specific impulses all worked out for you in nice little tables.

It also has some wonderful arficles debunking the "Club of Rome\'s" dire
predictions "Survival with Style" , "A Blueprint for Survival", and one of
he first accessible description of  Stephen Hawking\'s work on black
holes."Gravity Waves, Black Holes, & Cosmic Censors"

 > I think the MiGE/CoD universe would be a great place to play, but it
> needs a well thought out setup.  I don\'t think either Pournelle or
> Nivin rpg, or have any interest in rpging.  I\'d also lay you odds
> that they would want a nice hefty licensing fee to use their
> background in anything commercial.

Larry Niven seemed fine with other people writing in the "Known Universe",
there are quite a lot of people who have written "Known Univere" stories,
and authors in general aren\'t heavily into "licensing" their universes, they
are normally flattered if you ask to write something in their settiing, and
are really only concerned with whether you voiolate their idea of what the
universe is like, which usually means they ask for veto rights on
publication or at least some sort of editorial control..

> I don\'t even know if it would be
> legal to develop something non-commercial based on the MiGE universe
> for more than personal use.

There is nothing _illegal_ in people so doing .

Advertising or distributing it _might_ be preventable, but only if the
copyright holder pursues it, it\'s not specifically illegal, and it is up to
the holder of any rights to pursue and enforce them.

In fact, one can reuse someone\'s ideas without permission, because copyright
only covers the actual words in the book, _not_ ideas.

Of course, we should be polite and ask for permission anyway.

Frankie
