Sorry to jump in here, but I\'m a hopeless compulsive when it comes to
constitutional debates.  The "right to bear arms" has little to do with
crime rates, so your chicken vs. egg analogy has no bearing.  The right to
defend oneself against any threat is a basic human right.  Having the right
to bear arms and actually owning a gun are separate parts of the equation.
Separate, too, is the question of gun crime vs. other violent crimes.  The
reason there are more gun crimes in the US may be related to the fact that
there are more guns.  But the fact is, guns or no guns, there is more crime
in the US.  Probably has something to do with enforcing laws.  It takes only
a few days and very little money to make laws here, currently.  Enforcement
is much harder, more costly and more time consuming.  There are many other
social and cultural differences, as well.

