    'topic' => 'Diving depths : some data points (was BD crush depths)',
    'body' => 'Sorry to poke sticks at a dead thread.
The following RW info may be useful for comparative purposes :-

Depth,m  Notes
(metres -> feet : X 3.281)
20       limit for helmet divers (1930s)
40       typical breath-hold diving (e.g. pearl divers) ; 2 minutes
         dive time ; nitrogen narcosis breathing compressed air
         becomes a potential problem, especially with long dives
         (> 2 hours)
60       heliox mixtures required at and below this depth for dives
         greater than a few minutes in duration (\'bounce dives\')
120      WW2 submarine operating limit ; (heated) dry suits ; diving
         cylinders (e.g. Link type)
130      world record breath-hold dive (total dive time 2min 11sec,
         1996)
150      limit for \'hard hat\' divers (helmet divers, 1960s)
180      Bluefin tuna routinely dive to this depth
200      rough crush depth for WW2 submarines
282      Scuba-diving record (1994)
~300     approximate operating limit for modern nuclear subs
         (Soviet \'Alpha\' class able to dive deeper due to advanced
         hull?)
~410     Bathysphere (Dr. W. Beebe, 1920s)
~450     Seals observed to dive to this depth
600+     \'Jim\' (internal pressure = 1 atm) and \'Wasp\' suits (TTL 7-8)
         - have dived deeper than this ; crush depth ~800m
750      operating depth for the U.S. Navy\'s DSRV-1 and NR-1 ;
         ?crush depth
1000     Sperm whales have been observed to dive this far
~3900    \'Alvin\' bathyscape\'s rated depth
~4000    FNRS 3 (1954) - world record at the time
~6000    rated operating depth for underwater camera and robot
         platforms e.g. \'Argo\' and \'Jason\'
10911    \'Trieste\' (into the Marianas trench, 1960).


Robert O\'Connor
Medico, Gamer
