This is probably true.

>WITHIN the US, those states that moved to a "shall-issue" concealed carry
>permit system have always shown significant drops in assault, rape, murder,
>etc., while those municipalities and states that outright ban weapons always
>tend to have the highest murder rates.  Washington DC & New York City are
>prime examples.  Handguns are ILLEGAL in both, yet DC was the murder capitol
>of the US for many years. 

Bans on weapons in an area that has at the same time no restrictions on
movement of people and goods is meaningless. A ban on guns in Washington 
DC is meaningless if people are able to purchase guns in the neighbouring
states of Maryland and Virginia, for example. In NYC, they can cross the
river into New Jersey. Since there are no inter-state border patrols to
prevent people moving goods from one state to another, a ban on guns at
anything less than the national level is of absolutely no use whatsoever.

Note: I am not advocating such a ban (ie, at the national level) since I
don\'t live there in the first place... :)


