Getting back to the original post that started this thread in the first
place: a plea to have one day of no violence, not even in the media, as
some sort of symbolic gesture. The response was whether violence in the
media was a valid correlation with violence in society. We Canadians watch
the same violent movies and TV shows that you Americans do, but our violent
crime rate is lower. The Japanese watch movies and tv shows etc. that are
even more violent than ours, yet their violent crime rate is lower as well.
The only logical conclusion: there is no correlation between violence in 
the media and violence in society.

So all of those wanna-be do-gooders who think that getting rid of violence
in the media will solve the problem (like the people who are now lobbying
the entertainment industry) are barking up the wrong tree.

We just can\'t decide which is the *right* tree. I know where I stand on
the issue, but I am also willing to concede that the other side of the
argument may have a valid point. In the meantime, I\'m staying on my side
of the 49th parallel, where (for whatever reason) it\'s safer. :)

I don\'t suppose there\'s any more to be said on the issue...



