    'month' => '10',
    'topic' => ' The Alderson Drive -',
    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> There ae severe conditions to entering and leaving the continuum universe.
> to emerge from the continuum universe you must exit with precisely the same
> potential energy (measured in terms of the fifth force, not gravity) as you
> entered. You must also have zero kinetic energy relative to a complex set of
> coordinates that we won\'t discuss here. [note, I\'m not sure if this is just
> a handwave to avoid relativity, or if they really did come up with some set
> of coordinates - frankie]

Knowing Pournelle, they did.

> To get from the uantum to the continuum universe you must supply power, and
> this is available only in quantum terms. when you do this you turn yourself
> into a correspondence paeticle; go across the tramline; and come out at a
> point on the other side where your potential energy is equal to what you
> entered with, plus zero kinetic energy (in terms of the fifth force and
> comples reference axes [ there\'s that handwave again - frankie])

<snip>

> Travel by Alderson Drive consists of getting to the proper Alderson Point
> and turning on the Drive [ Note that the "technical" description implies
> there is a continuous "line" of such points between each pair of stars, but
> that seems to be ignored here - frankie]

I think that the Zero-energy & "complex axes" rules combine to make
only two points along the line possible entry/exit points. 

For example, consider the required "energy level" to be a plane. The
tramline between a pair of stars will only intersect that plane two,
one, or zero times. 

If it intersects twice, you\'ve got a pair of Alderson points. If it
intersects *once* you\'ve got a useless Alderson point (the zero-energy plane
intersects the fifth-force "surface" at the mid point of the saddle).
If it intersects zero times, then all of the saddle is below the zero
point level, and thus, there\'s no usable tramline between those stars.

