> Our party is about to enter the Sword Worlds cluster in our search for fame and
> profit. As a result, I\'ve got a couple of questions for the more economically
> minded members of the list.
> 
> How hard is it to use Imperial credits, OUTSIDE the Imperium?

There was a conversion chart for Imperial credits to \'local\' credits in \'Best 
of JTAS #1\'.  I\'ll chart it out for ya in a sec.

> The Sword Worlders (and for that matter the Darrians) have their own currency,
> right?

Seems logical to me.

> I assume that they conduct trade with the Imperium, so there must be some way to
> exchange currencies.

IMTU, PCs usually do currency exchanges at banks just \'outside the wire\' of 
the starport.  \'Inside the wire\', both local and foreign money is ok, though 
the locals tend to not give you a decent exchange rate.  <grin>

> Is the money traded like it is on our <rl> stock markets?

Beats me.  I never *could* figure out currency exchanges.

> Who sets the exchange rates? That is; how do they decide that a Swordworlder
> buck is worth half a credit or whatever?

On \'lawless\' worlds, the banks do.  On medium law worlds, the local gov does. 
 On high law worlds, the local gov does, but you can prolly get a *better* 
deal on the black market.  Just don\'t get caught!  <grin>

The chart:

                  Port Type
|----      
| TL |   A  |  B   |  C   |   D  |   E  |   X  |
- ----
| 15 | 1.00 | 0.95 | 0.90 |   -  |   -  |   -  |
| 14 | 0.95 | 0.90 | 0.85 | 0.80 | 0.75 |   -  |
| 13 | 0.90 | 0.85 | 0.80 | 0.75 | 0.70 |   -  |
| 12 | 0.85 | 0.80 | 0.75 | 0.70 | 0.65 |   -  |
| 11 | 0.80 | 0.75 | 0.70 | 0.65 | 0.60 |   -  |
| 10 | 0.75 | 0.70 | 0.65 | 0.60 | 0.55 | 0.45 |
|  9 | 0.70 | 0.65 | 0.60 | 0.55 | 0.50 | 0.40 |
|  8 | 0.65 | 0.60 | 0.55 | 0.50 | 0.45 | 0.35 |
|  7 | 0.60 | 0.55 | 0.50 | 0.45 | 0.40 | 0.30 |
|  6 |   -  | 0.50 | 0.45 | 0.40 | 0.35 | 0.20 |
|  5 |   -  | 0.45 | 0.40 | 0.35 | 0.30 | 0.10 |
|  4 |   -  |   -  | 0.30 | 0.25 | 0.20 | bart |
|  3 |   -  |   -  | 0.20 | 0.10 | 0.05 | bart |
|  2 |   -  |   -  |   -  | 0.05 | bart | bart |
|  1 |   -  |   -  |   -  | 0.01 | bart | bart |
|  0 |   -  |   -  |   -  |   -  |   -  | bart |
- ----

NOTES:

Imperial Credit is assumed to be a credit from a TL15 Starport A world for
purposes of exchange rates.

To exchange local credits to Imperials, multiply amount by conversion factor.

To exchange Imperials to local credits, *divide* amount by conversion factor.

\'-\' means that there is no planet of this particular starport and tech level
combination.

\'bart\' means there is no meaningful basis of exchange with this planet. 
Referees should determine the details of such a situation.

SERVICES:

Starport services are generally availiable at the local currency rate, including
costs for refueling, life support recharges, and berthing costs.  Maintanance is
also availiable at local costs *unless* the maintanance is done on a ship more
advanced than the local tech level could normally produce.  Example:  A TL12
ship lands at a TL9 class B starport for servicing.  Maintanance costs would be
paid as if the ship was instead on a TL12 class B starport planet.

BLACK MARKETS:

Sometimes governments set different rates of exchanges when exchanging
Imperials to local credits.  For instance, a planet having the \'normal\'
exchange rate of .40 might set the official exchange rate at .45 or .50 and
pocket the difference.  Changing local credits back to Imperials, you\'d use the
\'normal\' exchange rate of .40.  Unless of course, you go to the black market. 
<grin>  PCs can contact the black market in the usual ways, i.e., using
Streetwise skills.  How vigorously the local government suppresses the black
market depends on local law level, of course...

Keven

