When I was with the MFO in Sinai during the summers of 1986 and 1987, I
would go on pass to Eilat, Israel.  Buses arrived in Eilat from South
Camp at about noon every Friday.  Black market moneychangers would meet
the bus, and offer an exchange rate of (IIRC) 3.80 or 3.85 New Israeli
Shekels (NIS) per dollar.  The official exchange rate was NIS 3.70  to
NIS 3.75 per dollar.  Local shops, restaurants, and (most important to
young GIs) bars would accept dollars, but would usually round down to
NIS 3.50 per dollar.

ObTrav:  Replace NIS and dollar with local currency and Imperial
Credits, and you have a textbook example of the utility and limits of
Imperial Credits in a non-Imperial society.

