  {
    'body' => 'Dan Roseberry wrote:
> 
> I ripped off an idea today and I\'m looking for feedback:
> \'The General War\' ( a 5FFW variant)
> Setup:  Known Space 1107
> The 3I is the most powerful military, economic and political presence in
> known
> space. It has recently (in historical terms) defeated the Zhodani in
> 4FFW, kept
> Vargr raiders plus the Aslan Ihatiei at bay, decimated (for practical
> purposes) any dramatically serious insurgent movements in Solomani Rim,
> and generally has done everything right for itself since 1082.
> These objective realities have sunk in to the rest of the major powers
> in known
> space.... many are jealous of the successes that the 3I has achieved.
> Failures in the domestic or interstellar situation of these major powers
> cause  groups within them
> to lack dignity and self-respect. They look at the 3I and its successes
> and they
> become embittered, resentful, even enraged. As they see it, the 3I is
> being arrogant, rubbing their nose in it, seeking to dominate all of
> known space and beyond.
> 
> They decide to act. Sometime around 1107, every major power (Zhodani,
> Vargr(s), Aslan, Solomani, Hivers, and the K\'kree) prepares to launch a
> simultaneous attack
> on the 3I with the objective of destroying it forever.

In canon terms...not likely at all.

We have the following major polities: The 3I, Zho Consulate, Aslan (more or
less...the Heirate is the largest single political entity) The Vargr Rabble
(all 3,567.5 different political states in the Extents ;-), the Julian
Protectorate, the K\'Kree 2000 worlds, the Hivers, and the Solomani Confederation.

1)The Zhodani used the Frontier wars to keep the 3I at bay, more or less; they
never intended to _destroy_ the 3I, it serves as far too valuable a buffer
between them and the other intrestellar polities to rimward. The Frontier Wars
were _all_ feints on the part of the Zho\'s. They don\'t feel embittered or
resentful at all, quite the opposite. I\'ll bet the nobles on Zdant who
orchestrated the Frontier wars are pretty damn smug, in point of fact.

2)The Solomani Confederation fought the 3I to a standstill over the occupation
of Terra in the SRW. BOTH sides pretty much wore out over that one, and the
Solomani are busy rebuilding in their further rimward states, probably
struggling through serious economic problems. In the event of something
happening in the 3I, as in the Rebellion, they\'ll be back in there like
chickens on a June bug. The Solomani lost because they adopted particularly
inflexible tactics, and got spread too thinly.

3)The Vargr could never be expected to all work together...and if any of them
knew about the forthcoming attack, they would never be able to keep the secret.

4)The Julian Protectorate is the weakest of the several groups involved.
They\'ve enjoyed peace with the 3I for centuries, and have no reason to want
war with them at all.

5)Nobody trusts the K\'Kree, and with good reason....they tend to be genocidal
maniacs against you if anyone on your side likes to eat meat. If the K\'Kree
are in, count the Vargr, Aslan and Hivers, at the very least, out.

6)The Hivers wouldn\'t do it this way...they\'d manipulate the 3I to fall of
it\'s own accord...much bigger bragging rights doing it that way than
straightforward conquest. They also would not ally with the K\'Kree, or the
K\'Kree with them.

7)The Aslan would consider it utterly dishonorable, as it would mean
unilaterally breaking the treaty of Ftahir. The \'ihatei\' were never _that_
much of a threat...they are not reaving fleets bent on conquest. Most \'ihatei\'
invasions are far more like many immigrant groups in various parts of the
world. They buy or rent a bit of land, set up shops, work their butts off,
shop at each others stores, loan each other money, buy land, start taking over
certain industries, sponsor more of their members to the communities, and
soon, they\'re into the power structure, and they can buy more land, bring in
more ihatei, etc. Buying land is far preferable to fighting over it, much
easier, simpler, and by far a surer way of getting it. 

Another thing you\'re missing, here, I think. The 3I only appears bigger than
all of the other groups because all we see are the 3I-centric maps. All of the
major polities have occupied space that goes far beyond the fringes that show
on the 3I maps. 

Also, in point of fact, since the initial expansion of the 3I, and certainly
since the Civil War (400 or so) the 3I has not grown. None of the Frontier
wars have done anything to gain them more than a world or three. The Solomani
Rim War _lost_ them huge swaths of territory, since the Solomani Protectorate
broke away from the Third Imperium. The 3I managed to gain back _some_
territory, mosat notably Terra, but that was probably the bitterest, most
costly single campaign in Imperial history. 

I\'d wager that casualties taken in the siege and occupation of Terra ran,
easily, into the tens or hundreds of millions. In the billions of you count
civilian casualties...that was over one world. Granted it was a rather
_important_ world.

Here you\'re beginning to see the reasoning behind the Rebellion...internal
strife was the only way generalized all-out war would reasonably occur.

Finally, we have the end result, in the improbable event that what you\'re
describing does happen...what next? Each of these groups carve up the remains
of the 3I for themselves?

Go play Diplomacy a half dozen times or so to get a feel of what that kind of
conflict would be like...;-)
