>summers@alum.mit.edu

Having walked my share of picket lines (legally), I can tell you that there
are quite a few people out there who view any activity that impedes them as
wrong. A picket line (in a legal strike or demonstration) can legally slow
you down (although after five minutes they must allow you to proceed), and
yet I\'ve been run down by little old ladies who equate delaying them with
Nazism. (I kid you not!)

I also remember the Days of Action here in Toronto. On Friday there was a
violent incident at a picket line (someone rammed their car into the line,
and friends of the chap hit lost their tempers): Conrad Black\'s media
machine condemned the violence and said how it proved all lefties were
intent on destroying society. On Saturday there was no violence (protesters
brought their children and picnic lunches): Conrad Black\'s media machine
said how this proved all lefties weren\'t serious.

Still, I got a good media lesson out of it for a while. I taped the
coverage on Global, and could show my kids how the half-empty streets shown
on the news were actually filmed later, after the protest had been over for
two hours. (Did that by calculating the sun\'s elevation using shadows.) Led
to an interesting discussion about why _that_ film had been used, seeing as
Glbal had had a team on duty all day. Also noted that Global used a clip of
the police chief giving an estimate of the protesters, but did not show the
next sentence (where he explained that this was only those in a limited
area at one time, not the total number participating).

Oddly enough, our neo-con government has explicitly removed this type of
media literacy from the new curriculum.  Sometimes I agree with the
American view of government... then I remember that it is large
corporations who funded the election of this government (which rather
eliminates trusting private enterprise), which tends to leave me feeling
somewhat paranoid.
