    'index' => 'ec701',
    'body' => '>Date: Sun, 31 Oct 1999 09:28:35 -0700
>From: cos 90 <cos90@powersurfr.com>

>>>People who are opposed to abortion
>>>don\'t have abortions and leave other people alone.  I don\'t think people who
>>>yell at you or throw paint around outside of abortion clinics or fur stores
>>>should be attacked with flamethrowers.
>
>>line.  All sides need to obey the law.  But I think the idea that forceful
>>advocacy is a sign of moral inferiority is going too far.  Some of those
>>who oppose laws forbidding the peaceful picketing of abortion clinics are
>>veterans of the sixties who remember when such tactics were used against
>>them.

>Since when does yelling and throwing paint contstitute "peaceful picketing"?

Yelling is indeed peaceful picketing by the standards generally
applied.  It is also something that doesn\'t hurt anyone and shouldn\'t
be restricted.  Like I said, even many pro-choice advocates who remember
the tactics used against them in the sixties have taken this position.

Throwing paint is indeed a violation of the law and should be
dealt with.  But trying to use the tactics of a radical faction
to discredit an entire movement is a tactic that was wrong when
applied to anti-Vietnam War protestors and should be avoided
here.

>If all the protestors do is stand around outside with their signs and
>draw attention to themselves, I have no problem with that.

Others do.  Laws have been passed to limit this.

> The minute they
>start harassing others and/or try to interfere with people trying to get
>into the clinic, they are no longer engaged in "peaceful picketing".

I agree (as long as you are talking about real harassment and not simple
things like shouting your beliefs).  Even here there is some hypocrisy in
the world.  I know many people who see not problem with harassing scabs
crossing a picket line who get bent out of shape by anti-abortion
protestors.  The problem is that too many people are simply trying to limit
advocacy of views they disagree with.  Instead we should be trying to reach
a consistent definition of what is allowed and applying it evenly to all.
