    'body' => '>> > (okay, so the hospitals are free, the schools and universities are
>> >free, etc. And no, Denmark is not a communist state - it\'s just the
>> >way it is)

What I want to know is why would someone think Denmark was a
communist state?  Not because of the social programs listed or the
high taxes mentioned, surely!  Health care and higher education is
pretty close to being free in most of Western Europe and Canada
isn\'t it?  We might joke about it, but we really don\'t think Canada
*or* Denmark is a communist country.  Now, if you said that Denmark
has banned private ownership of property, especially productive
property, that would be a different story.  <g>

Feel free to ignore my personal opinions, but about the state
providing social services...  We all know these services aren\'t
*really* free.  So, you should expect higher taxes if the state is
paying for extensive social services.  At what level where this is a
good trade off (increased services for everyone vs higher taxes
assessed against everyone) is a debatable point that every country
has to make, but one that can exist in any mixed market economy
state.

I think one of the problems folks in the US have with government
provided services is that we don\'t perceive the services are (or
would be) worth what we pay (or would pay) for them.  The perception
may be right or wrong, but it is there.  Personally, I think it is a
size problem.  Public education through 12th grade is free and is,
for the most part, both locally controlled and financed.  Programs
that extend beyond the local or state level is where most people
have seem to strongly object. 

Ob Trav:  It appears that schools and universities are generally
free in the OTU as well.  Otherwise, PC\'s would have the strong
possibility of having outstanding loans after graduating.  Frankly,
I think, a lot of us play the medical system as being pretty much
free as well.  When\'s the last time you asked a PC for an insurance
card or denied them medical care until they paid, or showed that
they could pay for the care? <g>

Eris
