    'body' => 'Keven R. Pittsinger wrote:
> > Is the money traded like it is on our <rl> stock markets?
>
> Beats me.  I never *could* figure out currency exchanges.
>
> > Who sets the exchange rates? That is; how do they decide that
> > a Swordworlder buck is worth half a credit or whatever?
>
> On \'lawless\' worlds, the banks do.  On medium law worlds, the
> local gov does. On high law worlds, the local gov does, but you
> can prolly get a *better* deal on the black market.  Just don\'t
> get caught!  <grin>
>
> The chart:

First off, in RL most financial systems  partially  separate  the
stock market, bond market, commodities market, and forex (foreign
exchange or currency) market.  However, the forex market tends to
work much like the stock market ...  currency  is  fast  becoming
just another type of asset like a stock.

Currency is often abreviated to "ccy"
Exchange rate is often abreviated to "xrate"

Now there are two xrates: the PPP (purchase price  parity)  xrate
which is used by economists to compare  different  countries  GDP
figures (etc), and the market xrate which  is  used  by  everyone
else when buying and selling ccy.

The PPP xrate is  the  rate  that  *would*  exist  if  goods  and
services had a universal price.  For example if a range of  goods
cost USD 10,000 in the US and the same goods  cost  GBP 6,000  in
the UK then the PPP xrate would  be  USD 10  =  GBP 6  (or  about
USD 1.67 per GBP).

The market xrate is xrate the free market thinks  it  should  be.
As a rule of thumb developed nations tend to have a market  xrate
similar to their PPP xrate, where as third world  countries  have
market xrates of 75% or even as low as 50% of their  PPP  xrates.
However the actual market xrate will bounce  around  this  figure
based on speculation much as stock prices bounce around.

In anything other than a planned economy (socialist states,  etc)
the market xrate is set by the free market.  In planned economies
the xrate is set by the planetary government ...  and  where  its
rate differs from a free market evaluation there will be:

1) a "black market"
2) a preference amongst locals for non-local major ccy
3) an impediment to international trade

Note that banks (etc) typically quote the xrate with their  mark-
ups already added in (thus they quote a  separate  buy  and  sell
rate for each ccy).  The difference  between  the  buy  and  sell
xrates is called the "spread".

The chart given only begins to make sense if you think of  it  as
giving the xrate in local credits ... where there are N local ccy
units ("bucks", "quid", "yen", whatever) per local credit.  N  is
a relatively stable but otherwise random number.



