    'date' => 'Mon, 1 Nov 1999 12:16:39  0800 (PST)',
    'body' => 'On Mon, 1 Nov 1999, Charles Collin wrote:

> I think alot of people out there got the wrong idea from this post.  The
> point of "A Day of Peace" is to have a day where violence is not performed
> in any way.  The idea is not that TV shows cause violence, but that by
> watching and enjoying images of violence we are somehow celebrating it,
> and it would be good if we did not do this for just one day.  Too many of
> you had a kind of knee-jerk reaction where you reflexively hugged a
> variety of constitutional amendments to your chests.  This has nothing to
> do with that.  The "Day of Peace" movement is not anti-gun nor anti-free
> speech.  It is anti-violence. 
> 
I do not care to have my reaction characterized as "knee-jerk" when I have
thought these issues through long before this piece of internet spam made
its way into my box, Charles.

Violence is a part of the human nature.  I believe that by censoring it
you drive it into the underground where it can only come out even worse.
I\'m not willing to do that even for one day.  I\'m tired of the notion that
we can improve ourselves by cutting off bits.  Violence is necessary, it
is what impels us to defend our loved ones and family and selves when
required.  I am not anti-violence.  I am against the misuse of violence,
but I will never become the sort of person that is so against violence
that they\'d allow their spouse to be raped, for example, rather than
fight.  Violent movies, for the most part, celebrate heroism-- the person
who endures violence in order to defend or help others.

And I think this is a well-intentioned, but ultimately very bad, idea.

Kiri
