Perhaps you\'re right, but I read it differently. Upon reading it again, I\'m
convinced that it\'s not my critical faculties that are at fault. The piece
is clearly an appeal to the audience to practice entertainment
self-censorship for a day, with the unspoken "what if" assumption that this
act would help to curb violence in general.

To make things even more confusing, there is no yard stick by which to
measure what is meant by "violent content", which is interesting since what
does and what does not constitute "violent content" is still hotly debated.
What\'s worse is that the scenario outlined in the piece that Jason forwarded
doesn\'t take into account the possibility that certain books, television
programs and movies make use of "violent content" in hammering home a
message that is distinctly anti-violence.

>Too many of
>you had a kind of knee-jerk reaction where you reflexively hugged a
>variety of constitutional amendments to your chests.  This has nothing to
>do with that.

This has plenty to do with the First Amendment, since it advocates
"voluntary" censorship. Why would participation in this act have any
importance at all otherwise? A boycott of any sort is always intended to
send a message to those who profit from what is being boycotted. In effect,
this piece is saying that you should send a message to television networks
and movie studios that you will not tolerate "violent content" under any
circumstances. That\'s fine if you really believe it will help, but
apparently this message was passed on to a group that, for the most part,
doesn\'t.

It has plenty to do with the Second Amendment since the only form of
violence that is explicitly mentioned in the text happens to be gun
violence. It\'s a subtle way of associating being anti-gun with being
anti-violence, regardless of what that term might actually mean.

>The "Day of Peace" movement is not anti-gun nor anti-free
>speech.  It is anti-violence.


The problem is that "anti-violence" in today\'s American vocabulary means (if
you identify with the left) "anti-gun", or (if you identify with the right)
"anti-free speech".

This piece leaves us with the burning questions of what constitutes
"violent-content" and exactly what end this piece hopes to attain by the
actions it advocates.
