    'body' => '>I have never heard of the five minutes rule; however, I do know that getting
>in someone\'s face and screaming is legally considered assault-- I was told
>this when my lawyer advised me to take a restraining order out against
>someone and I said, "but they\'ve never hit me" and he said "They don\'t have
>to!"

In Canada, a picket line must be moving, and it may not obstruct people for
more than five minutes. The usual laws regarding assault still apply (to
both picketers and line-crossers).


>I do not actually think that picketers should be allowed to obstruct people
>physically because it comes too close to behavior that borders on assault
>and I prefer there to be less of a gray area.

Depends on how you define "obstruct", doesn\'t it?  If you say "move" and I
am s----l----o----w----l----y moving, am I obstructing you?  What if I\'m moving,
but the chap behind me is following so close that you can\'t slip between us
(and so on)?  If you push through, are _you_ assaulting _us_?  (After all,
we\'re just walking around the block.) That\'s why Canadian law defines a
legal limit (for the whole line, not per protester): anything longer than
five minutes _is_ obstructing, and grounds for having the line shut down.
I think it\'s a reasonable compromise, because I can\'t think of very many
cases where someone whould absolutely need to cross a line in less than
five minutes, and these can be handled by simple negotiation. ("Look, I\'m a
doctor and there\'s someone with a heart attack in there"  qualifies; "Look,
I\'m a lawyer and I have to make a phone call" doesn\'t.)  There are lines
where this doesn\'t work, and there are legal methods for shutting those
lines down.


>I may not think that they are Nazis but as Cynthia said, there are lots of
>ways to convey a message to such a degree that no one will ever want to hear
>it.

Yup.  But I find it ironic that exercising my legal and democratic right
should somehow make me a Nazi. According to this woman, we went to war so
that people would follow their leaders!  (I wonder who she thinks won,
anyway.)


>ObTrav:  I wonder about different protesting styles in the cultures of the
>Third Imperium.  How do the Vilani protest ANYTHING?  Do the Vargr and the
>Aslan even have demonstrations?  Do the K\'Kree throw paint on old ladies in
>furs?

Vilani?  No idea, but if they do all the permits are in order. A question
for the TravCulture list, I think.

Vargr? Yes, definately. Part of a leader\'s charisma is how big a crowd
follows you.

Aslan?  Probably not. Individual Aslan will act as their honour dictates,
including challenges to _personal_ duels. (One reason we have mass
demonstrations is that the ordinary person feels a need to group together
against the massed force of the opposition.  If your average British Green
protester could challenge the chairman of Monsanto, it wouldn\'t take long
before Monsanto listened to local opinion.)

K\'kree? Paint? Stomp them into the ground.  (Parenthetically, the first
time I see an animal rights type throw paint on the leather jacket of a
biker, because they oppose killing animals for clothing, I\'ll conceed that
they are serious about their beliefs.)
