A case in point:  I work in a very high-pressure software company (is that
redundant?), in which members of different groups often have grossly
different and frequently conflicting priorities, just due to how quickly
things change and management\'s inability to keep things coordinated.  As a
result, despite everyone doing their best, tensions and resentments can
run very high.

So, several evenings a week, we all play Quake for a couple of hours.
Firing a salvo of rockets at fleeing members of the Marketing team has
calmed my nerves and soothed my anger many, many times.  It\'s hard to say
from obviously anecdotal evidence, but I think our Quaking has helped
significantly in making our company work better, and the people in it
happier with themselves and each other.

It\'s hard for me to reconcile this with the view that violent video games
(and movies, and so forth) cause real violence.  I think it\'s more the
opposite.  After all, movies have never been bloodier, and ultra-violent
and realistic immersive games are new this decade, but violent crime in
America continues a precipitous multiyear decline.  And as others have
mentioned, in Japan, where the content is even more horrific, the society
is less violent.

My take on the whole affair is that we are suffering from yet another side
effect of the all-seeing media eye.  These days, when a few whacked-out
kids shoot up their schools, all the world knows about every detail,
instantly, exhaustively, for weeks.  There\'s no escaping the story, and
the impression "kids are shooting up our schools" gets into the collective
psyche despite the fact that 99.99999% of our kids are in fact *not*
shooting up our schools.  A hundred years ago, there were mass murders in
rural America that make for stomach-churning reading, but few people knew
about them, and *nobody* outside the legal system knew as much about them
as we all would if they happened today.

