    'body' => 'On Mon, 1 Nov 1999, Charles Collin wrote:

> <Kiri>
> is what impels us to defend our loved ones and family and selves when
> required.  I am not anti-violence.  I am against the misuse of violence,
> but I will never become the sort of person that is so against violence
> that they\'d allow their spouse to be raped, for example, rather than
> fight.  Violent movies, for the most part, celebrate heroism-- the person
> who endures violence in order to defend or help others.
> </Kiri>
> 
> The fact that you consider rape wrong means that you are in fact
> anti-violence.  Otherwise, what rule is their to condemn this act? 

The fact that it is a violent act which is not being committed in order to
defend oneself or someone else.  I believe that those are the right uses
of violent behavior.  I think that people who decide not to defend
themselves or their loved ones are complicit in what happens to them,
because they could have done something to stop it, but chose not to.

> Because it is a "misuse of violence"?  What constitutes a "proper use of
> violence"?  Maybe lynching the guy you think committed the rape?  This
> sort of justification has led to all sorts of innocent death.  All
> violence is a misuse of action.  Defending yourself is sometimes the best
> course of action available, but that doesnt\' make hurting your attacker a
> "good thing".
> 
I very much disagree.  I don\'t think that we should be teaching people
that you can rape, kill, loot, misuse innocent people and nothing will
happen to you.  When you refuse to defend yourself and those who depend on
you, you are letting the world know that your own life and the lives of
those you love are not worth the discomfort to your conscience and stomach
that doing something about it would cost you.

If someone comes into my house bent on harming me or my loved ones, I can
and WILL defend myself and those I love or go down fighting.  That way,
whatever happens, I\'ll know that I did my best to take care of myself and
the people I love.  And if my attacker gets hurt, maybe it will make him
think twice.  If my attacker gets killed, perhaps in his next life he\'ll
be more cautious.  Call it removal from the game for unnecessary
roughness.

Violence is a part of human nature.  I believe that human nature is
basically good.  Violence, like all other parts of human nature, has its
place.  Rape and other acts of unwarranted violence are wrong; not because
they do or do not occur in the animal kingdom (you brought that up, not
me) but because we are intelligent enough to be the master of our nature
and to use all of its parts appropriately rather than suppressing them or
letting them run hog wild.

I personally like human beings.  We are capable of horrific atrocity, but
show me an animal who can create so much beauty...

Kiri

