    'body' => '>Many believe that humans have an intrinsic need for an outlet for violent
>emotions.  By releasing such emotions through violent but non-destructive
>ways may it may be possible reduce the actual destructive violence.  One
>interesting theory is that exposure to representations of violence (art,
>music, movies, etc.) may be a sufficient outlet for these
>emotions.  Following this theory, in order to limit violence, this "Day of
>Peace" should encourage people to watch the most violent possible movies
>instead of actually hurting other people.

If this were true, there would be fewer fights after a sporting event, not
more.

What seems to happen, according to Watson (in "Dark Nature"), is that the
folks who\'s team/boxer/whatever won go home happy, and the losers go home
and pick fights. (Note: this is a statistical thing, like hot weather, and
applies to groups not individuals). Vicariously winning seems to remove the
need to win in a conflict, vicariously losing leaves all the original
aggression entact.

I strongly urge people to read "Dark Nature". I found it an excellent book
on the biological components of evil. Think of it as a cross between
science and philosophy. Even if you don\'t agree with Watson (and I do),
you\'ll get a lot of neat ideas for Traveller cultures out of it.
