    'index' => 'ec814',
    'body' => 'Robert Prior writes:
<snip>
K\'kree? Paint? Stomp them into the ground.  (Parenthetically, the first
time I see an animal rights type throw paint on the leather jacket of a
biker, because they oppose killing animals for clothing, I\'ll conceed that
they are serious about their beliefs.)
</snip>

OT:  Not all "animal rights types" are paint throwers.  Some of us simply
believe that animals, like humans, have the capacity to feel pain, and that
insofar as one can avoid it, it might be nice not to inflict it on them.
Neither myself nor anyone with whom I choose to associate would dream of
tossing paint at someone wearing fur, leather, or an aluminum-foil helmet
bedecked with antlers.  For that matter, I don\'t preach to my
carnivorous/leather-clad friends, including my wife, who would probably
choose to personally chase down and kill her own wildebeests rather than
adhere to my diet.  I consider my choices to be my responsibility, and
while I\'d certainly like to see other people choose the same things I do, I
learned (fairly late in life) that I haven\'t a lot of control over that
sort of thing. This doesn\'t make me any the less "serious" about avoiding
cruelty, I don\'t think.  There are responses to ethical values other than
promotion... instantiation, for instance.  One can promote peace by
launching surgical strikes against nations that would wage long and bloody
wars with their neighbors, or one can instantiate peace by living
peacefully.  Sort of the difference between the Policeman of Democracy and
your local Quakers.  Anywho, sorry about the long OT... occasionally though
I have to speak up when people assume I\'m a hypocritical fruitcake because
I don\'t want to eat a steak.  I\'m a hypocritical fruitcake for other
reasons entirely.  ;)

Otter Driver
