Well, I would think that the doctrine of "ignorance of the law is no
excuse" only applies to laws whose existence is known to those to whom
the law applies.  After all, if there has been _no_ public notice
(however obscure) that using Monkeybagels to prepare one\'s taxes is
illegal, then one cannot be prosecuted for filing a Monkeybagel tax
return.  OTOH, if all certified public accountants have available
information that Monkeybagel tax returns are illegal, then any CPA who
files a Monkeybagel tax return _could_ be charged with violating said
law.  The CPA\'s client would be liable if either he/she/it could have
learned from outside sources that Monkeybagel tax returns were illegal,
or he/she/it ignored the advice of the CPA not to file a Monkeybagel tax
return, and did so against the advice of someone who was in a position
to know the law on this matter.

[BTW, see the following Web site [or SJG\'s Daily Illuminator for 1 Nov
99] for an explanation of Monkeybagels:

http://www.monkeybagel.com/monkeybagel.html      ]

If there is, in fact, a valid law or regulation against contact with
extraterrestials, then that law or regulation should only apply to those
who could have known of it.  In other words, if I\'m not _allowed_ to
know the law or regulation, I shouldn\'t be held liable for violating it.

***WARNING:  The above is not intended to be construed as legal advice. 
The above-posted information is only a layman\'s view of common sense.***

