    'id' => undef,
    'date' => 'Tue, 2 Nov 1999 20:32:18 +1300',
    'body' => '> > to emerge from the continuum universe you must exit with
> > precisely the same  potential energy (measured in terms
> > of the fifth force,  not gravity) as you
> > entered. You must also have zero kinetic energy relative
> > to a complex set of coordinates that we won\'t discuss
> > here. [note, I\'m not sure if this is just
> > a handwave to avoid relativity, or if they really did
> > come up with some set of coordinates - frankie]
>
> Knowing Pournelle, they did.

The thing that makes me suspect this is that it seems to imply  a privileged
reference frame, which at the time they wrote this was not considered
particularly acceptable physics..

While I suspect that what they may have meant is zero kinetic enrrgy
relative to some axes that map the two Alderson points at each end of the
jump, I _think_ this this still implies a privileged reference frame, as I
_think_ it implies that if you can have zero kinetic energy relative to both
of these two points then somehow these two points must also have zero
kinetic energy relative to each other, and how can a "point" in space (as
opposed to a particle) actually have kinetic energy ?

Then again, this sort of stuff is a bit beyond me.

It would make more sense to me if they had said "must emerge at a point that
has the same gravitational  (or "fifth force" ) _potential_ energy"  rather
than actual kinetic energy.

But that\'s probably because it\'s sort of how the drive we wrote for our own
space game worked, you were precipitated out of jump when your "kinetic"
energy was cancelled by the force of the "anti-gravity" well of the star you
were heading for. The higher the gravitational potential energy, the harder
it was to translate, but once translated the "antii-gravity" of the nearest
star, (possibly affected by planets ) accellerated you rapidly away from the
current star, and then you cruised until you hit your target star. If you
missed you\'d keep going until you hit a gravity well capable of stopping
you.  Oh, and you could "bounce off" an "anti-gravity" well if you didn\'t
hit it dead on, and get accelerated away again if you never slowed down
enough to emerge.

What this meant was that the closest to a gravity well you went into jump,
the faster you went, but also the more energy it took to make the
transition. This would seem to imply jump stations on planet would be the
best, but we had the jumpers maintain the kinetic relative to the target
star they had on translation, which meant jumping planet to planet, while
theoretically possible, was too dangerous.

Also, as planet\'s affected your course in jump, it required extremely
accurate knowledge of the target system to aim at a planet, aiming at the
star was a _lot_ easier , and missing by even a little could result in
travelling onward to somewhere else.

So, the use of jump as a weapon was possible but very unreliable, and of
course if you did it to someone , they\'d do it to you.

The other thing we liked was that there was a theoretical upper limit to how
far you could jump from a star, but it was limited by the size of the star
and the amount of power you had, not some arbitrary technology.  All of a
sudden, dense stars took on strategic significance, someone positioned at a
neutron star had a much greater operational range, assunming they could
generate enough power.

Frankie







> > Travel by Alderson Drive consists of getting to the proper Alderson
Point
> > and turning on the Drive [ Note that the "technical" description implies
> > there is a continuous "line" of such points between each pair of stars,
but
> > that seems to be ignored here - frankie]
>
> I think that the Zero-energy & "complex axes" rules combine to make
> only two points along the line possible entry/exit points.
>
> For example, consider the required "energy level" to be a plane. The
> tramline between a pair of stars will only intersect that plane two,
> one, or zero times.
>
> If it intersects twice, you\'ve got a pair of Alderson points. If it
> intersects *once* you\'ve got a useless Alderson point (the zero-energy
plane
> intersects the fifth-force "surface" at the mid point of the saddle).
> If it intersects zero times, then all of the saddle is below the zero
> point level, and thus, there\'s no usable tramline between those stars.

Yes, that makes sense.

Frankie
