    'from' => 'Timothy.Collinson@solent.ac.uk',
    'body' => 'Robert Prior wrote:
>The Ontario government has come up with a new grading system for school
>students. It is roughly as follows:

>level 4 - exceeds expectations (>90%)
>level 3 - meets expectation (75-90%)
>level 2 - meets many expectation, but not all (60-75%)
>level 1 - meets bare minimum of expectations (50-60%)


I\'m a bit mystified by this.

Surely the \'expectations\' are what you expect (i.e. what you are assuming
they\'ll be able to achieve rather than some future event you\'re looking
forward to).

In that case, how can they meet a \'bare minimum\' of expectations?  If
they\'ve met the minimum, haven\'t they \'met expectations\'?  (If only just).



My apologies if this is a stupid question.  I must be good at them.  I just
had my 15 seconds of fame last Thursday when I appeared (very briefly) on
the BBC\'s _Question Time_.  They had just spent 10 minutes debating the
issue of our House of Lords being radically changed.

One lot were arguing that it should be appointed (by the House of Commons -
the \'main\' half of the UK parliament); the other lot were arguing that it
should be by election.  (Some were arguing for a bit of both).

Right at the end of this segment before the \'referee\' David Dimbleby moved
onto another topic entirely, I couldn\'t resist putting my hand up.  Maybe
I\'ve been too long on the Traveller Mailing List but I thought there were
other options.  I asked why no one seemed to be considering competition
(e.g. a group of sportsmen selected by athleticism; exams for academics; a
group of clergy....) or by lottery?  I\'ve never heard the media or anyone
put forward anything like this, so what am I missing?  Why is this not
being considered?  Is it somehow a \'stupid\' idea?

The \'referee\' evidently thought very little of my question as he kind of
dismissed it with the comment: "or elections".

Is it just a failure to think \'outside the box\' or am I thinking of weird
Traveller possibilities and failing to see that in RL this isn\'t feasible?
(I wasn\'t suggesting I had a fully worked out solution, just querying why
no one even brings it up.)

Just curious (and a little embarrassed).




Back to Rob\'s email:
>Professional note: if we use your idea, I\'ll make certain that you get
>co-author status on our report.


If TML get going on this - is it going to look like one of those things
written by 100 people or more?!


tc
