>born run off and
>become Ihatei, "driving their ships to new lands"(Zepplin Rocks!). Does
>this not cause a
>big depopulation problem? The only fix I can think of is that there must
>be an awful lot
>of Aslan.

No, since, for the most part, only first sons will be breeders anyway...
And remember, Aslan are Polygamous, not polyandrous (Multiple wives, fine,
Multiple Husbands, no)... so those with the land get to breed, as they can
afford to support a wife. At least pre-space. Then, consider that the birth
rate is supposedly something like 5:2 Female to Male, and typical
landowners will begat 1-3 children on each of 1-4 wives, and you have a
sudden population problem.

Also, since Male Aslan Ego is tied to land, the non-heirs (due to
primogeniture, hehehehe) need land. In order to get useful land, you have
to leave the hierate. In order to properly support wives, you have to have
land.

>Now then, there is the Treaty of Ftahir. Canon says (correctly) that it
>would be very
>dishonorable for the Aslan to break the treaty. Ok. When the Rebellion
>occurs, it is now
>honorable to break the treaty because of the death of ONE (quantity 1)
>Aslan? What did
>they do before the Rebellion, when I am very sure allot more Aslan died
>from all manner
>of bad events in the 3I?

The aslan shot was a Clan Ambassadore, the (in the aslan view) literal
Honor-Bearer for the whole of his clan. Killing him was, to the aslan mind,
the same as attacking the whole clan, not just the Aslan. Additionally,
said attack was without honor, and there also was no clear emperor to
appeal to for redress.

Aslan view lords AS the government to a certain extent, according to a
variety of sources... hence, no Emperor, No Imperium. No Imperium, No
Treaty of Ftahir.

Thus, you have an entire clan\'s honor slighted, no means of redress without
conflict, and a logical assumption that the "Lord" of the treaty has no
heir, and thus the body he was lord of ceases to be a body...

As for the others, they didn\'t carry the Title of Ambassador for a Clan,
get mowed down without challenge, and then be quietly ignored (I\'ve not
seen any reference to Dulinor sending an apology to the Ambassador\'s Clan
in the cannon); Until a Clear Emperor exists to mediate, Dulinor makes
reparitions or dies, or someone else negotiates a new treaty, that entire
clan has it in for Dulinor.

Think (based upon the early Contact! article in JTAS) of Aslan Honor much
like Feudal Japanese Honor, as portrayed in literature...
	Insult the man, he seeks revenge.
	Insult the family, The who Family seeks revenge
	Insult the Daimyo, and flee his wrath.
	Insult the Emperor, Prepare for war.
	Insult a man\'s representative, and you have insulted
		the man himself as well.

