>
>Hi -- I can\'t post reliably to the TML, so please pass this on for me, as
>well as passing it on to Steve Jackson (who I\'m reluctant to email out of
>the blue since he probably gets all kinds of garbage from rabid fans).
>
>A couple inaccuracies, or at least misleading implications:  First, the
>citation in the article is a perfectly clear citation to the Code of
>Federal Regulations, and one which can easily be checked if you know the
>standard notation and have access to a copy of the CFR.
>
>Second, the article\'s suggestion that the material cited is somehow buried
>in an obscure location is no more true than for any other Federal
>regulation; the claimed cite places it a bit more than a third of the way
>into the regulations governing NASA, which is a reasonable place for it to
>be. Granted, the CFR is huge, but people generally know the parts they
>need to.  Why is it in Title 14?  Because that\'s where all the aeronautics
>and space stuff is (the criminal code is Title 18).  Heck, NASA\'s
>nondiscrimination provisions -- which the Feds would want everyone to hear
>about -- are at Sections 1250-1252.  The NASA Seal is described in 1221.
>The author didn\'t know jack about how Federal regulations are catalogued,
>is all.
>
>Finally, the regulation as quoted would, by the normal legal rules of
>interpretation, be seen as applying *only* to NASA missions.  The fact
>that the word "only" is not used in the statute does not provide the
>"loophole" the article editors claim.  There\'s a legal maxim that
>enumerating specific cases excludes cases not enumerated.  A statute
>requiring that all dogs be leashed could not, for example, be extended to
>cats or parrots by the argument that it didn\'t say "only dogs;" had the
>drafters wanted to extend it further, they could have done so explicitly.
>(And we won\'t even get into the question of whether NASA would even have
>had the authority to apply it anywhere else; scope of administrative
>agency powers is an arcane field.)  Why am I bothering to discuss this?
>Read on...
>
>It is true that the statute referenced in the article does not currently
>exist; Title 14 (Aeronautics and Space) goes from Section 1210
>(Development work for industry in NASA wind tunnels) to Section 1212
>(Privacy Act - NASA regulations), leaving Sec. 1211 labeled as "Reserved".
>
>I dug a little farther, though.  The LEXIS-NEXIS service makes archive
>copies of the CFR available back to 1981.  In the 1981 version, Section
>1211 *does* exist, and is substantially as reported, with the heading
>"Extraterrestrial Exposure."  (I\'ve attached a text copy of the actual
>statute to this email.  TMLers who want one can email me directly.)  Its
>purpose appears to be to allow NASA to quarantine personnel who come into
>contact with extraterrestrial material -- remember that at the time of the
>early moon missions, there was concern that astronauts might come into
>contact with diseases against which our population would be defenseless.
>The provisions last appear in 1991, and are absent from 1992 onwards.
>
>So... the law did exist, but it doesn\'t now, and it was never quite as
>far-reaching or secret as the author of the article would have us believe.
>That\'s the way conspiracy theories usually are, in my experience. But
>where did it go, and why?  Now, that\'s the question...
>
>Joe Saul (Michigan Law School \'99, NASA Space Life Sciences Training
>          Program \'86, Traveller player since \'78)
