    'date' => 'Tue, 2 Nov 1999 07:17:55 PST',
    'body' => 'In mail you write:

>> > to emerge from the continuum universe you must exit with
>> > precisely the same  potential energy (measured in terms
>> > of the fifth force,  not gravity) as you
>> > entered. You must also have zero kinetic energy relative
>> > to a complex set of coordinates that we won\'t discuss
>> > here. [note, I\'m not sure if this is just
>> > a handwave to avoid relativity, or if they really did
>> > come up with some set of coordinates - frankie]
>>
>> Knowing Pournelle, they did.
>
> The thing that makes me suspect this is that it seems to imply  a privileged
> reference frame, which at the time they wrote this was not considered
> particularly acceptable physics..

Well, when you get right down to it, you *have* to have a "preferred
frame" if you want FTL *unless* like like messy stuff like time travel.
The equations just don\'t let you have FTL *and* relativity *and* strict
"local casuality". So you need to break relativity. And a preferred
frame is one that does minimal damage if you do it "right". 

> While I suspect that what they may have meant is zero kinetic enrrgy
> relative to some axes that map the two Alderson points at each end of the
> jump, I _think_ this this still implies a privileged reference frame, as I
> _think_ it implies that if you can have zero kinetic energy relative to both
> of these two points then somehow these two points must also have zero
> kinetic energy relative to each other, and how can a "point" in space (as
> opposed to a particle) actually have kinetic energy ?

Sure. "Zero kinetic energy" is a fancy way of saying "at rest". So they
just can\'t be *moving* relative to each other in the fancu co-ordinate
system. 

