    'from' => 'mickb@iinet.net.au',
    'body' => 'After a (cough) brief hiatus, we now return you to our irregularly broadcast
schedule...


As usual, I make no claims as to the ability of this data to withstand the
attentions of the Canon Inquisition.  Your  mileage may vary...



11 - Hideki (Admiral Hideki Morimotu)
- -2080 to -2018
reigned -2029 to -2018

Having seized the centre of power and emasculated the Council of Noble
Officers, Hideki was forced to deal with the regional and provincial powers
in order to secure the throne. During his rule, the provincial Naval
commanders forced Hideki to reconstitute the Council of Noble Officers as a
body with somewhat more clout than he had envisaged.  furthermore, the
Council was now composed almost exclusively of provincial commanders and
governors, forever breaking the power of the General Staff at the highest
levels of Imperial politics.

Hideki survived no less than nine recorded assasination attempts during his
rule before dying of heart failure in -2018.  After his death, the rumour
that his demise was the result of a tenth, successful attempt persisted.


(Vidmar) (Vice-Admiral Vidmar Kulkinski)
- -2059 to -1973
anti-Emperor -2028 to -1973

While Hideki\'s coup was successful in the fact that it ended with him on the
throne, he was unable to wholly eliminate opposition on Hub/Ershur.  A small
number of relatively junior General Staff oficers managed to flee, and were
joined by other discontents as they established a \'government-in-exile\'
outside the Imperial borders in the Ley Sector.  The following year the
survivors formed their own Council of Noble of Officers and elected Vidmar
Kulkinski as \'true Emperor of the Rule of Man\'.  This government-in-exile
was a fairly palrty thing, and lived under the constant threat of
elimination by Hideki.  It was saved only by Hideki\'s need to come to terms
with fractious provincial leaders, some of whom gave covert aid to the
\'anti-Emperor\'.  While scholars today discount the legitmacy of Vidmar\'s
claim, it is leant some legitimacy by the actions of subsequent Emperor\'s to
\'reform\' the anti-Emperors (also known as the not-Emperors, Little Emperors
and petty-Emperors).

12 - Elize (Admiral Elize Papete)
- -2064 to -1997
reigned -2018 to -1997

As Governor of Trans-Zarushagsar Province and Viceroy of the Verge Worlds,
Admiral Papete was one of the more powerful  leaders of the slowly
splintering Rule of Man.  During Hideki\'s rule, Elize largely governed
Trans-Zarushagaar as an independant state, paying little attention to the
central government on Hub/Ershur.

Following Hideki\'s death, the Council chose Elize to succeed him, knowing
all too well that her rule would continue to encourage the centrigual
tendencies that had characterised the last half-century of hte Rule of Man.
Elize herself looked upon the Imperial throne as a largely ceremonial title,
and spent much of her time in her provincial capital (Elize retained the
Governorship of Trans-Zarushagaar when she ascended the throne).  Government
on Hub/Ershur was delegated to Admiral H\'sui Shen Liang, the vice-Governor
of Hub/Ershur Province (as Empress, Elize was niminally governor of
Hub/Ershur as well as Trans-Zarushagaar).
