    'body' => 'Charles Collin writes:
<snipped>
>As for correlational stats, one thing I\'ll always remember is
>the assertion by my most recent stats teacher that "A .2 or .3
>correlation means nothing, that\'s just the background correlation
>of the universe".
<snipped>

	That\'s an interesting way of putting it.  On the other hand,
	there are a few issues to be considered.  A statistical
	correlation can be computed for most any two variables,
	an it will rarely be zero (indicating no correlation), even
	when the variables are entirely unrelated.  This is due to
	random variation in the variables.  Of course, if the
	variables are related, the computed correlation will tend
	to be farther from zero.  The statistical question is then
	"what is the probability that I could have found a
	correlation this strong if, in fact, there is no
	relationship between these variables?"  For typical samples,
	a correlation of 0.2 to 0.3 would not be uncommon when the
	variables are unrelated, but for very large samples even a
	correlation of 0.1 might be statistically significant.
	Whether such a relationship is significant to anyone will
	depend on the variables and the reason for the analysis.

Peez
