    'body' => '(Disclaimer: I am an attorney, but none of the
following is to be taken as legal advice (nor is
anything else I may say on the TML or elsewhere
without specifically identifying it as such in
response to a request for legal advice from a
client).)

We\'ve been talking about whether or in what situations
ignorance of the law excuses violating the law.  The
answer depends mostly on the type of society. 
Societies that strive to protect individuals against
the government (like the USA, as only one example)
generally require that laws be part of the public
record, accessible to anyone, before they can be
enforced.  The idea is that it is not fair for
individuals to be unable to know what conduct is
prohibited or regulated.

Other societies may have laws that are secret, and it
may even be a crime to know the contents of those laws
without proper authorization.  In this way, the
citizenry are kept afraid that they are unwittingly
committing crimes, and the police can always accuse
them of criminal conduct and use that as leverage to
obtain an advantage.  ("Comrade Shopkeeper, I\'ve
examined your books and records, and there appear to
be violations of the secret currency laws.  I will
allow you to put them in order, and I will return in
two days to review them again.  I am sure that they
will be in good order at that time.  In addition, I
would like to enjoy the company of your daughter
between now and then. Do we have an understanding?")

A related issue is highlighted by the following
extremes:

Everything not prohibited is allowed.
Everything not allowed is prohibited.
Everything not prohitibed is mandatory, and everything
not mandatory is prohibited.  

Which extreme more closely describes the society in
question?

- --Glenn

