    'body' => 'The weapons ban in the UK would be considered extreme by many other
countries. It is far easier to say what is permitted than what is banned -
for instance we are not permitted to carry clubs.

We are allowed to carry knives with a blade less than 4 inches in length,
but not any form of flick-knife, drop-knife or clasp-knife (where the blade
can be released one-handed, in effect).

We are allowed to wear rings provided that they are not clearly for
offensive purposes (so, no spiked rings or joined rings like
knuckledusters).

A few people - mainly farmers - are allowed to use shotguns.

We are allowed to use airguns.

If we are found to be carrying even permitted weapons in public then the
police can charge us with carrying offensive weapons, although they have to
prove we are likely to use them in a fight. We are not permitted to carry
any weapons uncovered. There has been protest at the changes, particularly
from target-range shooters like myself. However, the vast majority of the UK
public approve of these laws.

