I\'ve toyed with the idea of something along parallel lines (though not the 
same; the two could be combined). Through history, \'guilty until proven 
innocent\' is much more common than the reverse. A society could extend this 
in an extreme way: all citizens are assumed to have committed some crime 
that the government has not yet learned of. Thus, they can be detained 
and/or searched at the whim of the police as the person is obviously guilty 
of some criminal act. Of course, those in the government would, for the most 
part, have to be assumed \'guiltless\' (or at least as one rose in the 
heirarchy, one proved oneself less guilty).

