    'index' => 'ed053',
    'topic' => 'RE: Border Guards',
    'body' => 'Dear Folks -

Danny asked:
>ObTrav:  How common is the non-self incrimination right in planetary law?
>Is it a low law level concept, high LL concept, or does it span both?
>Is it allowed in Imperial Law courts?

Wow, I might actually know the answer (since I only just read George Herbert\'s
"Law in the Imperium" article in Challenge).

There are High Justice and other Imperial-level crimes, recognised crimes, and
planetary crimes. Imperial courts (subsector/sector level) only hear the first.
They allow extradition/deportation for recognised crimes, but only if the planet
actually has the crime noted ("recognised") in their legal system. The last
level is up to the planet, and the Imperium won\'t help send someone back to face
a planetary charge (there are always bounty hunters, however...).

With Imperial-level crimes, ther is no restriction on evidence. The person can
incriminate themselves, info can be gleaned second-hand, from wire-taps,
whatever. It is up to the court whether it accepts or rejects each piece of
evidence (and the article even included MT tasks for presenting evidence).

As to planetary jurisdictions, it\'s up to you. After all, each member world is
free to govern itself, right? Some might use the familiar prosecution-defence
model (with or without a jury), some might use the Napoleonic (European)
accusatory model, and so on.

[Disclaimer: I am not a lawyer, nor do I play one on tri-dee. I only play them
in Traveller. Well, only as NPCs anyway.  ;-)  ]
