I have once used a very interesting punishment system in a campaign. On
a high-tech, fairly unremarkable law, the PCs ship got stolen and taken
for a ride that ended in a crash, rendering it unusable. They went to
the local court of law, bringing the thief (who survived by leaving the
ship using a grav-belt) with them, hoping for an easy method of payback.

What happened later was a large source of frustration for the PCs. The
court found out that the thief had a small starship of his own. They
therefore ruled that since the thief had wrecked the PCs craft, the PCs
got to choose between wrecking the thief\'s ship or claiming it as their
own. They complained loudly, since the ship they would get was a lot
less expensive, and they wanted money to make up for their loss. The
court complained about their time being wasted, and the PCs eventually
had to leave, now as owners of a primitive trading vessel.

Oh, and one more thing. When they wanted to leave the system, their
takeoff permit was delayed a few hours, as per the court\'s instructions.
This was the punishment for wasting the time of the court.

I doubt that they will ever go to that system again :-)

I case you haven\'t figured it out, the whole story was partially
designed to remove the PCs ship (rather high tech and powerful) from the
campaign in a way that wouldn\'t upset the storyline. Turned out to be
really funny...   *wicked grin*

