I\'m going with the government edubabble -- sorry, but my brain isn\'t up to
translating all the time.

Roughly, level 3 is fully meeting all expectations for a student in that
course. Level one is meeting a bare minimum of expectations: more mistakes,
poorer vocabulary, and so forth, but still enough work successfully done to
give them the credit.

The problem, of course, is coming up with exactly _what_ the expectations
are: something the government has not done, even though they have been
loudly claiming that they have standardized expectations. For example, my
department spent hours writing the expectations for a grade 9 science lab.
Parents loved it: nice and detailed, clearly lays out what we expect, and
so forth. Problem is that other schools use different standards, because
the government hasn\'t provided any.An inner-city school might have decided
that some of our level 1 items were in level two (or even three): without
going through the 74 different marking points you wouldn\'t know what the
differences were.


Leaving aside all elements of standardization, supposedly _every_ student
who gets a credit can perform every required level one expectation -- or
not, because the government is still deciding how to take a whole series of
individual marks and produce and agregate summation.


ObTrav: How do people handle professional qualifications?  The original
Traveller had, for example, Medical-3 making the character a doctor
automatically. While fast and simple, having spent some time trying to get
qualifications recognized in other parts of the same country (let alone in
other countries), I think the following might be more interesting:

Rather than a character automatically getting a qualification if they have
a certain skill, they must pass a test. In some cases (eg. graduating from
a professional school) this happens during character generation. After CG,
a character must "write the test" to get the qualification.

Some qualifications will _only_ be available to characters studying them
formally. This may reflect the esoteric type of skill, or may be simple job
protection on the part of the official licensing body. (For example,
Ontario paramedics must study in Ontario: the colleges no long administer
competency exams for out-of-province paramedics, because that reduces the
jobs available for their graduates.)

Some qualifications will be available for characters who have studied
formally elsewhere, on simple reciprocity. (Eg. engineering credentials
between provinces.)

Some qualifications will be available to characters who have studied
formally elsewhere, and who also pass a skill test. (Eg. nursing in Canada.)

Some qualifications are available to anyone who can pass the test. (Eg. a
driving license.)


Naturally, the test may have little relationship to the actual skill, or
the successful candidate may simply be lucky, or good at taking tests,
or...  This leaves the referee free to hit the players with an engineer who
could pass all the written exams, but can\'t deal with real parts in an
emergency; a medic who can pass the multiple-choice exam yet faints at the
sight of blood, or a medic who is more skilled than a doctor but doesn\'t
have any formal qualifications...


Exactly _which_ catagory a qualification/certificate falls into is,
naturally, dependent on the setting and the referee.

Assumign that you like my idea, what qualifications would be recognized
across the Imperium? Which ones would be purely local?
