> manufacturing base, or stuck on a tech 7 or so world with the bare minimum
> of gear and were builing your own arsenal. what about caseless? Could one
> go this route to simplify things, or does this just add more
> complications? Are caseless rounds more difficult to manufacture?
> Personally I\'ll stick to a .22, as the ammo is ubiquitous (sold on the
> counter at local stores) and cheap, and I don\'t like big boom.

In a word: Yes.

Caseless ammo needs a propellant that is structually strong enough to 
not need the case, as well as being water,petrol and sunlight 
resistant. If it is to be used in a miltary situation it also has to be 
very cook-off resistant, as there is no case to soak up and extract 
waste heat from combustion. Also the primers are trickier to make as 
they have to burn up completely. Not only that but the weapon has to be 
better made as there is no case to seal the chamber.

The G11\'s ammo was actually made from a high explosive mixed with a 
stabilser, as normal rifle propellants just wouldn\'d cut it.


