> These are all based loosely on my rl experiences building a large
> distributed computer-controlled heating, ventillation, and air
> conditioning (HVAC) system. 
>
> * Telltale bulbs are shoddy; one or two burn out every day.  Engineer
>   gets twitchy from scanning areas and not seeing greens where she
>   expects them...wonders if it\'s the green burned out, or the yellow,
>   or...
>
> * Readouts are hard to read, unstable, or require special handling to
>   use.  Analog gauges might require a tap on the side or a slight shake to
>   settle to true readings.  Digital readouts disappear or go to all 8s at
>   unpredictable times.  Maintenance and repair tasks become a level harder
>   and take twice as long.
>
> * A \'routine\' wiring repair turns weird when an unknown component is found
>   behind a panel.  It\'s an old, battered-looking circuit box with various
>   cables recognizable as power and data to various systems, along with two
>   unlabled ones nobody has ever seen before, clamped onto a series of
>   rusty-looking terminals.  The box isn\'t mentioned on the maintenance
>   contractors\' records.  Prying it open in place (which risks dislodging
>   one or more of the poorly-attached cables) reveals a set of primitive
>   power conditioning and surge protection circuits...a function which
>   should already be handled elsewhere in the wiring.  Emphasis on the
>   *should*...
>
> * ...because power spikes start showing up in the ship\'s grid, at
>   unpredictable branches and times.  Mostly they just burn out lights
>   and trip breakers, but there\'s always that worry that one of the
>   breakers will be familiar with Murphy\'s Law.  Eventually, it turns
>   out that the spikes happen only when the door to the captain\'s
>   fresher is opened or closed.

And from an old post here (or possibly elsewhere), upon removing panels
to repair battle damage (or the once in a lifetime meteor strike that
pentrates the hull), you discover that the <bleep><bleep><bleep>
automated wiring robot that did that cable run had used some gizmo you
don\'t have to ID the wires in the cable by sending signals thru it. And
*hadn\'t* used color coded wires. Thus:

You "dissect" the ends of the broken cable so you can splice the broken
wires. Only to find yourself staring at 200 wires, all the same color. 

If you know the tricks, it\'ll take a couple of assistants and a few
dozen or so measurements on *each* of the two cable "segments" just to
establish that there are no open or shorted wires. If you *don\'t* know
the tricks, it\'ll take some ungodly number of measurements (200
factorial?) 

And if you didn\'t think to label the wires as you did that set of
tests, you\'ve got to do another set of as many again to ID the wires.
*Then* you can get down to splicing them. Have fun!

