I can\'t remember who wrote this series of short stories (Niven maybe?) 
about an eclectic professor that helped the cops in some obscure 
investigation, but in that world they had a mind probe that could reliably 
tell whether someone was lying or not.  Police could compel it\'s use in a 
criminal investigation, but the law was that a person could only be 
subjected to it once in his lifetime (some sort of weird double jeopardy 
extension).

The result was that criminals would line up to get arrested and probed for 
a minor crime, knowing that no matter what they did afterwards they\'d be 
safe from the probe (and with the probe available, juries seldom convicted 
without probe evidence).  As a result, the police internal policy was to 
only use it if they were already certain the person was guilty...

