***NOTE:  While I, as an Arabic linguist, have learned about some
aspects of Islam, the following should not be taken as representative of
the Islamic faith, nor should it be construed as authorizing or
encouraging deviation from Islamic tenets among Terrestial Muslims.**

Well, unless the ship is within a few parsecs of Terra, the direction to
Mecca can be approximated by the direction to Sol from the ship.  In
jumpspace, I would interpolate the direction to Sol, based on the
following:

1.  The direction to Sol from my Jump initiation point;

2.  The direction to Sol from my Jump terminus;

3.  The direction to Sol in jumpspace, interpolated from the first two
directions, and based on time elapsed in jumpspace.

Again, unless the ship is within a few parsecs of Sol, the fractions of
a degree would be slight enough as to make no difference.  Besides,
should interstellar travel become commonplace, I would expect that those
Muslims who would undertake such would know that God (Allah) would
accept the intent, and not expect _perfect_ precision in directing
prayer to Mecca.

I would expect that recycled water would not be considered kosher,
unless all personnel aboard the ship were Jewish adherents to kosher
dietary law (I base this supposition on the fact that, when I dined with
Israeli Defense Force personnel, they had color-coded plates for Jews
and Gentiles, so that Orthodox Jews would not fear eing defiled by
eating off a plate that had been used by a Gentile.)

As to how one determines the Islamic calendar dates while outside the
Solar system, I would expect that, within sight of Sol and her planets
(in M:1100, that could be quite some distance), direct observation of
Sol, Terra, and Luna, plus calculation of light\'s travel time from Sol
to the point of observation, would fulfill the requirement for "direct
observation" of the new moon.

Besides, at least some Islamic rules (such as daytime fasting during
Ramadan) are relaxed for those who are travelling, especially when
travelling in service to the Islamic faith.

Again, I would expect that Muslims who would be outside of the Sol
system would receive appropriate guidance from (fairly flexible) Islamic
scholars, so that they would not be in violation of Islamic law.

Of course, the _real_ problem, for Muslims in the 3I (especially prior
to the Solomani Rim War), is the requirement for pilgrimage to Mecca
(Al-Haj).  Even after Terra falls to Imperial forces, travel to Mecca,
and the return trip home, could take half a lifetime or more for Muslims
in the Spinward Marches.  It wouldn\'t surprise me if Islamic scholars
established shrines throughout human space that would suffice to fulfill
the pilgrimage requirement, without having to travel for a decade or
more each way on one\'s pilgrimage.

