> impressed I am with the Air Farces of the world.

I presume you\'re refering to strategic use of airpower, here; I think we
can all agree that tactical aviation has been hugely important as an
element of the combined-arms doctrine since WWII.

The major problem with strategic airpower has been its misapplication,
particularly since WWII.  In that war, massive, well-coordinated raids on
German production and transportation centers significantly damaged
Germany\'s ability to field an effective army.  In the absence of the
multiyear bombing campaing, it\'s quite probable the invasion of France in
\'44 would have been repelled.

The flip side, of couse, is that we could have continued to bomb the
continent for a decade and Hitler (or his successor) would still have been
in power without the necessary followup to the air campaign -- that is,
sending staggering numbers of ground troops across the channel to get shot
to pieces on the sand, all too often, with the remainder securing those
beaches, then the ports, and spearheading a ground drive into occupied
Europe. 

This is the strategic side of combined arms -- you can\'t (usually) win a
large modern war on air *or* ground strategies alone.  The problem is, air
campaings are very cheap and easy for the party with air superiority, and
you\'re so visibly \'doing something\'; so there\'s a strong temptation to
stop at that point without committing ground troops to exploit the
weakening brought on by your strategic campaign.  Which leads to outright
losses like Viet Nam, and ambiguous pseudo-successes like Kuwait and
Kosovo.

