Ask Japan how significant the American air force can be in winning
a war.

Germany had an interesting situation at this time. Right up until then,
the Nazi regime had been unable (or unwilling) to militarize much
of the civilian economy. Household goods were still being produced,
much of the city economy was devoted to civilian service industries,
they were even still importing foriegn labor to act as housekeepers. 

Then American bombers leveled much of the German urban centers.

Munitions and other military plants were quickly rebuilt, due to the
needs and resources of the government. Many heavy machine tools
proved difficult to destroy, even when the building surrounding them
was badly damaged, and the important machines could be moved
with relative ease. 

Cabarets, beer gardens and department stores were not rebuilt - and the 
workers who had been employed there had to find other work, many at
the new weapons plants.

In this regard, American airpower acted to force the German economy
more strongly towards a war footing, which, though more efficient, probably 
had a significant morale effect on the civilian populace.

The biggest victories of the American strategic bombing command
were in the attrition of the German transportation networks (especially
rolling stock) and the serious interference with German lubricant and fuel 
production. 

The German Jet Fighter program, though they fielded operational units, 
spent most of it\'s time on the ground due to a lack of essential supplies, 
and by late 1944 many German tank formations were operating with little 
or no fuel reserves on hand. This lack, coupled with Germany\'s serious
transportation problems, was a crucial element in the American and
British ground combat successes in the West (as well as the Soviet
successes in the East).

ObTrav: Pick your targets carefully when black warring a world. One
barrage of missiles, at the right target, can be worth a week of ortillery
strikes. The atmosphere generation plants may be very well defended,
but what of the factory that supplies it with spare parts?

Walt Smith
