    'body' => 'Actually, since the National Guard is funded and regulated by
the Federal Government, and controlled by the Federal Government
in large measure, it is pretty clear that it is not even close
to what the Founders intended.  Reading the Federalist Papers
and other \'explanatory\' essays put out by the Founding Fathers
to explain the new Constitution to the masses, it is clear that
the intent was for an individual right.  The controversy today
really boils down to \'Do we interpret this amendment based on
intent or based on current opinions?\'  For the record, I am
firmly in the \'intent\' camp and I strongly support the
individual right concept.

Hoping to avoid another 2nd Amendment flame war and to bring
this back to Traveller: The Imperium does not have a
Constitution, but it has \'Founding Declarations\' of some sort -
establishing the Moot and other conventions of Imperial
Structure.  The Imperium is also heavily bound by non-written
tradition (The Right of Assassination, forex).  Are these things
interpreted against \'modern\' opinion, or are they interpreted
based on the original intent?  The Right of Assassination seems
to be a developed tradition that appears well after the Imperium
is founded, but it could actually just be an old (Empire of
Man?) tradition that has resurfaced.

In a oligarchial society like the Imperium, I think that Intent
would not really be as strong a factor for interpretation, due
to the absolute power of the Emperor (I, Cleon, declare that the
Right of Free Assembly applies only to persons with full heads
of hair, and only on Tuesdays); Tradition would be a much
stronger tool of social influence.  In a more democratic
society, the level of attention paid to Intent would be (IMHO)
the thing that places that society on the scale of
Representative Government to Mob Rule (not organized crime mob,
of course).  Those societies that interpret and implement laws
based on Intent would tend more towards a formal representative
or republican government, while those societies that reinterpret
issues more and more often based on common opinion would be
those that tend toward the true Demos-style democracy where
everyone votes on everything.

On a practical level, Travellers will find pretty much evey
combination or interpretation you can imagine, and traditions
will vary so widely that Intent would not have a very important
influence on how things go when travelling across the secotr.
But for those Travellers who are heavily involved in the
government of one world (members of the aristocracy etc), this
could be very important.  How much can you bend the rules and
get away with it?  If you do bend the rules, is this likely to
change the rules in the future, or just be seen as an aberration
to be punished or ignored?  Most Travellers see law and custom
on a world in terms of \'What weapons may I have or buy here?\',
but that little UPP number does not tell the whole story.

Steve Charlton

