> I hope, that you realize, that Germanys highest armarment output was in
> 1944.  So much for strategic bombing. 

This rather misleading statistic often appears when this subject is
discussed.  Yes, production in tons of steel peaked in 1944.  That\'s why I
phrased my statement the way I did.  There\'s more to "field[ing] an
effective army" than producing a lot of tanks, arms, and ammo.  For
example, you have to fuel the vehicles, and lubricate them, and move the
troops to the front(s), and supply them there, and so on and on.  It was
this infrastructure that strategic bombing most heavily damaged, resulting
in a situation in which the Germans had a great deal of materiel which
they could no longer effectively deploy in the field.  Petroleum shortages
proved especially devastating, and these stemmed in large part from
wholesale destruction of fuel storage and transport facilities.

> Since Douhet the airforces have claimed to be able to win wars. Evidence
> gathered on the ground has always shown this claim to be exaggerated. 

My industry (software) suffers from the \'silver bullet\' theory as much as
the military does.  Every new technology is hyped to the skies, and is
predicted to solve all problems and revolutionize the field.  Then the
hype dies down, and people gradually discover how this new tool works with
others already in the box.

Air forces don\'t (usually) win wars, but were I a ground soldier, I\'d much
prefer to wade into a hostile country whose ability to wage war has been
degraded through a prolonged bombing campaign.  If the enemy is mounting a
counterattack, it\'s more effective and cheaper in lives lost to destroy
the rail stock and line they will use to reach the front, rather than
shooting the enemy soldiers individually once they get there.  And so
forth.

> Even now in Serbia/Kosovo most of the military material claimed to be 
> destroyed by air raids was just maskirovka stuff.

And yet, however ineffectually airpower was applied, and however timid
allied forces were about ground deployments, an air campaign did result
(eventually) in partial capitulation by the Serbs.

Desert Storm provides a somewhat better model for how air and ground
forces complement one another.  The prolonged air campaign left the allies
with total air superiority, and also (and this is critical) seriously
damaged the Iraqi C3I and supply infrastructure.  This weakened the Iraqi
military to the point that when the ground attack came, victory was swift
and relatively bloodless (compared to most predictions).

