    'body' => '> At 07:53 PM 11/3/99 -0800, you wrote:
> >When you have a *reliable* indicator of whether a person is or isn\'t
> >telling the truth, the protection against self-incrimination takes on a
> >whole different character.
> >
> >You are more likely to run into limitations on what sort of questions
> >can be asked under which circumstances.
> 
> I can\'t remember who wrote this series of short stories (Niven maybe?) 
> about an eclectic professor that helped the cops in some obscure 
> investigation, but in that world they had a mind probe that could reliably 
> tell whether someone was lying or not.  Police could compel it\'s use in a 
> criminal investigation, but the law was that a person could only be 
> subjected to it once in his lifetime (some sort of weird double jeopardy 
> extension).
> 
> The result was that criminals would line up to get arrested and probed for 
> a minor crime, knowing that no matter what they did afterwards they\'d be 
> safe from the probe (and with the probe available, juries seldom convicted 
> without probe evidence).  As a result, the police internal policy was to 
> only use it if they were already certain the person was guilty...

In H. Beam Piper\'s universe (\'Little Fuzzy\', \'Uller Uprising\', et. al.), there was a machine called the veridicator, which was part of every police interrogation as well as being installed in every courtroom to determine the truth.  As long as the globe showed red, you were telling the truth *as you knew it*.  The instant it started turning blue, you were in deep kimchee...

Piper\'s writings on colonial laws was fairly interesting as well.  In \'Little Fuzzy\', one guy remarked that they could only execute him once, and the other guy said, \'Well in <legal cite that escapes me at the moment>, they shot the guy dead, *then* hung him\'.  Interesting...

Keven

