    'body' => '> Date: Thu, 4 Nov 1999 12:07:32 -0500
> From: Walter Smith <SmithW@HARTWICK.EDU>
> 
> In the Traveller Law Level abstraction, a Low LL planet should have few
> things the police get involved or interested in, and therefore the police
> will not be involved unless it\'s serious (and probably very public)
> wrongdoing. If you\'re walking down main street, blazing away at 
> innocents with your trusty laser rifle, the corrupt or non-corrupt nature
> of the local peace officers isn\'t as relevant, or will at least be very
> difficult to conceal.
> 
> Compare this to a very high LL world where very minor and very private 
> things can be criminalized. Once the offense is private and difficult to
> detect, the very existance of the crime can be a judgement call on the 
> officer\'s part. Then we *do* get into situations where corruption is very 
> relevant. 

Good points.  On the converse, though, a low LL world might not have
strongly enforced policies on how what cops exist operate.  In other
words, yes, they would certainly react in force to the madman with the
laser rifle on Main Street, but they might have more de facto or de jure
discretion on whether to respond to (say) a commercial burglary, or a
barroom brawl.  Under these circumstances, "justice for hire" could become
the norm; if you want the police to get involved in a "borderline" case,
you pay them, above or below the table.

Aha!  I just realized how this works out.  At low LL, you pay the cops to
get involved.  At high LL, you pay them to leave you alone. :)

