    'month' => '11',
    'topic' => 'GT Starship gearheadedness (kinda long)',
    'body' => 'Hi all. I\'m at home sick today, so I thought I\'d play with GURPS Traveller\'s
starship construction sequence. I\'m putting together a CA-15 Cruiser Armored
from FSotSI, and I\'ve run into suprisingly few problems, but for the
following:

1) Nuclear Dampers. I can\'t, for the life of me, find what a nuclear damper
is supposed to do in the starship combat system. The CA-15 has an Optimized
Damper, so I assume that\'s one module with 10-mile coverage. But what does
that translate to in the combat system?

2) Spinal mounts. Oh, those spinal mounts. The CA-15 has a NPAW model T,
which is roughly twice the size of the NPAW listed in the book (3,000 spaces
v. 1500 or so), so I\'m going to have to build one. I started by trying to
reverse-engineer the NPAWs in the book, but found that I couldn\'t get the
numbers to match! Oh, I get the stats all right, but I can\'t seem to make it
fit in the mass and space alotted. I come up with:

   Weapon: 11853 tons mass, 2370 spaces (948 if you use cf/50
      for volume instead of cf/20 as per GUPRS Vehicles, pg. 42)
   Full Stablization: 115 tons mass, 237 spaces (95)
   Power Plant: 1898 tons mass, 152 spaces
   Energy Bank: 32 tons mass, 1 space

For a total of: 13898 tons mass, 2760 spaces (1196).

As far as I can tell, it requires no crew stations -- as a hull weapon, it\'s
fired from the bridge by the chief gunner or pilot (as per GT pg. 150). What
am I missing here?

3) Armor. Why is total surface area the area of the hull plus the *total*
area of all the ships turrets and bays? I would think that, since the
turrets and bays are at least partially imbedded in the hull, they wouldn\'t
count as surface area. Bays especially, since they are now almost completely
*inside* the hull.

That\'s all I can think of right now. I like the system overall.

BTW, the GT CA-15 looks like it\'s only going to have a maneuver of 2Gs or
so. With an AV of 80 (DR 30,240), it\'s got a lot of armor.

Ciao,

Joseph R. Dietrich
