Besides the National Guard there are two levels of Militia in the United 
States, the State Guard and the unorganized Militia.  The State Guard also 
known as the State Military Reserve is for use only as a second line 
militia in the state of origin and may not be used outside the state 
without state permission.  It is equivalent to the British Home Guard of 
WWII.  In most states it is at a cadre level at best in peace time (San 
Diego, California\'s unit is the 41st Inf. Bn.).  The last time it was 
called up in California was in WWII when it was used to patrol the coast 
and guard bridges and defense plants using men exempted from federal 
service for fitness, age, job, or completion of military obligation.  The 
unorganized militia consists of all fit for service men between 18 and 
50.  The last time this was called out was during the Civil War.  Short of 
a total disaster it won\'t be called up active duty for the same reason that 
County Sheriffs don\'t use their power of involuntary Posse duty, it would 
be political suicide.  Very few men realize that they have a 8 year 
military obligation in the United States.

Jim Brewer
