I\'m going in the same direction as Doug, but still
point out that it depends largely on what you\'re
bombing.  Aerial bombardment of civilian targets has
not hastened the end of any war, nor hindered the
target\'s ability to fight.  Aerial bombardment of
military targets can incapacitate them, allowing
ground forces to defeat them.  Two examples of the
latter phenomenon are the Gulf War and the invasion of
Europe by the Allies in 1944.  

A possible counter-example to the first statement --
about the ineffectiveness of bombing civilian targets
- -- is the nuclear bombing of Japan in 1945.  Years of
fire- and explosive bombing of Japanese cities had not
hastened a surrender nor even much prevented the
Japanese from supplying their forces.  The nuclear
attacks, however, caused an immediate surrender.

