    'topic' => 'A Well-Regulated Militia (new thread title)',
    'body' => 'When I was young, I took the "well-regulated militia" bit of the Second
Amendment to be redundant with the National Guard.  Then I learned some
more history, which put a whole different spin on that amendment and
actually changed my stance on gun control:

First, at the time, the newly-minted United States didn\'t have a standing
army.  There was, in fact, a fair amount of sentiment AGAINST the concept.
So the theory was that whenever there was need, the able-bodied men would
pick up their rifles, go out and do what had to be done, and then return
home and go back to their lives.  Switzerland still seems to operate on
this concept.  The militia IS the army.

Imagine if we had no Army, just the National Guard, period.  (Well, then we
wouldn\'t be the Policeman of the World, just like back in Teddy Roosevelt\'s
time.  Duh.)

Second, and part of the reason the people didn\'t want an army (hint:
military coup), was that they\'d just fought a war to free themselves from
one unpopular government.  The right to bear arms was, as far as I can
tell, intended to be a guarantee that if the citizenry got sufficiently fed
up with the new government, they could get together and overthrow it too.

For obvious reasons, this interpretation is not appreciated by those who
are currently in charge, but it\'s very popular among the various "militias"
with an axe to grind about the gummint.  Also, the balance has changed a
bit:  no longer can you count on both sides having the same kind of weapons...

ObTrav:  I dunno... a world where after every (quite peaceable) election,
the outgoing politicians are ceremonially escorted from their offices by
armed members of the populace?


- ----
