    'body' => '> From: Craig Berry 
> There\'s more to "field[ing] an effective army" than producing a lot of
> tanks, arms, and ammo.  

The Soviets had a lot of problems along these lines in 1941.  They had more
tanks than every other country in the world combined, and most of their
tanks were still fairly effective, that is, not obselete by 1941 standards,
but they had no spare parts.  The result was that equipment that broke down
couldn\'t be repaired, and mostly had to be abandoned.  By the end of \'41
they were down to about 3000 tanks, out of an initial fleet of 30000.  The
Germans were down to about 300 effectives, out of an initial 3000 or so.

This situation arose largely because the economic planning mechanisms they
used rewarded the production of complete tanks, but not parts.  I\'m not
sure they ever really got around this problem.

Other stuff around this topic:
Australia wasn\'t bombed much during WWII, but by 1944 its economy was in
desperate shape.  Since the US was bearing the brunt of the war in the
Pacific then, about half the Australian armed forces were demobilised, in
order to rebuild the economy.  As an example of the economic chaos, the
railways/railroads in Queensland had to be pretty much rebuilt after the
war, as the locomotives, rolling stock, track and so on had been run into
the ground, with little maintenance having been possible.  (My grandfather
was a rail worker during the war.)

A thought:  does anyone know much about the role the Chinese played in
WWII?  How much of the Japanese military did they keep busy, compared to
the amount fighting everyone else?  If you want a huge military force built
on minimal resources, the Chinese might be the people to look at in this
period.

Another thought:  The second bloodiest war in history (after WWII) was the
Taiping Rebellion in China in the 19th century.  (I\'ve fouled up the
Romanisation of "Taiping", of course).

OBTRAVs:
(1)  When fighting the Vargr, keep a close eye on your supply lines.

(2)  Civil wars on hi-pop worlds can be quite as nasty as small
interstellar wars.

(3)  The Solomani might have had problems sustaining their war effort in
the Rebellion.  In particular, worlds like those in the Near Bootes Cluster
might have experienced huge economic dislocation.  This might, in time,
tend to limit their enthusiasm for the war.

(4)  General problems of production and supply in wartime.  

(5)  In situations like the Frontier Wars, the worlds close to the action
would go onto a war economy footing, but it seems unlikely that the rest of
the Imperium would.  Basically, the Imperium would usually fights its wars
with one arm tied behind its back.  The Rebellion, of course, is the great
exception, but even there, many worlds would probably have tried to avoid
it, or the change would not have occurred until several years into the war.
 The chaos caused by the militarisation of the economy might have
contributed to the Hard Times, as civilian facilities get pushed lower and
lower on the repair priority list, and so on.

Alan Bradley
