codes and the atmosphere codes, to see which one the author used as
the main modifier for hydrographics.

It appears that the hydrographics codes are based on the world size, if only
because there are a fair number of "impossible" results if you assume that
they were based on atmosphere.  There are "impossible" results if you
assume they\'re based on size code, too -- but nowhere near as many. 
Also, although I didn\'t do a formal statistical analysis, the distribution of
differences "size code - hydro code" appeared closer to the expected
normal curve than the distribution of "atmos code - hydro code." 

So what it looks like to me is, Mr. Harshman (or whoever) followed the
original Book 3 rules, *mostly*.  The places where those rules are violated
appear to have been deliberately chosen.  At least they are uncommon
enough that I think I can account for them when doing the capsule
writeups.

I feel better now.

- ----
Jon F. Zeigler: Mathematician, computer geek, amateur historian, freelance
writer, occasional scribbler of bad poetry
