    'topic' => 'Re National Guard and other millitias',
    'body' => '>Besides the National Guard there are two levels of Militia in the United
>States, the State Guard and the unorganized Militia.  The State Guard also
>known as the State Military Reserve is for use only as a second line
>militia in the state of origin and may not be used outside the state
>without state permission.  It is equivalent to the British Home Guard of
>WWII.  In most states it is at a cadre level at best in peace time (San
>Diego, California\'s unit is the 41st Inf. Bn.).

In texas, it is "the Army of the Republic of Texas"... the only "Standing"
army belonging to a State. The Texan Army never disbanded, it simply became
a militia.

> The
>unorganized militia consists of all fit for service men between 18 and
>50.  The last time this was called out was during the Civil War.  Short of
>a total disaster it won\'t be called up active duty for the same reason that
>County Sheriffs don\'t use their power of involuntary Posse duty, it would
>be political suicide.  Very few men realize that they have a 8 year
>military obligation in the United States.

Very few have read the selective service regs, either. When you enlist, you
enlist for X years active duty, y years inactive ready reserve (where you
can be recalled to duty on a whim), and X+Y= 8years, measured from latest
REENLISTMENT... (I read the fine print very carefully... besides, I know 8
or 9 people who were recalled during Desert Storm, including a SFC (Sgt,
1st class)  who\'d RETIRED... and a SgtMaj who got recalled after retiring
about 3 years ago for a period of 6 months.... And the last time the
unorganized militia was called out was Vietnam... via the selective service
program (aka, the Draft). And, based upon that process, if the unorganized
milita is called up, they can keep you for duration plus 6 months, or 8
years, whichever is longer.

Ob Traveller: IMTU, there is no standing Imperial Army below the Army
level; said units comprise an "Army" HQ per world, with a unified COACC,
Army, and Wet Navy HQ based upon each world, An Army Group HQ per subsector
or minor polity, and a Sector Army HQ per sector. The "Imperial" forces of
each world are called into Imperial Duty when needed, and affixed to the
appropriate HQ. Note that officers transferred to imperial service in the
HQ\'s may not serve in the "Imperial HQ" for their world of origin. The
"non-imperial" forces are like state organized militias: they only serve
off world by order of the world government... Note that an HQ for an Army
Level organization is probably about a battalion, and would include a lot
of enlisted specialists. I came to this based upon the material in COACC
(for MT, by GDW)... but I\'d been leaning towards it anyway.

Also Ob Traveller, under such a system, how common would it be for the
really adventuresome to hop to a nearby major world to get into a mroe
prestigious army???

