I like this, and nothing in GDW-Canon contravenes this. IIRC, doesn;t M0
include some "Framing Documents"??

>This is an interesting point, what is the real, explicit and implided
>powers of
>the Emporer, Dukes, Nobles, Moot, Beuros, Military and others. Could a
>Planetary
>Noble use \'1975 Reserve Powers\' to dismiss a duely elected planetary
>government
>who\'s polacy is anti imperium? Can A planetary govenment appeal to a subsector
>or sector duke for an appeal aginst a unfavorable desision? Is the Moot or
>Emperor the final level of appeal?

IMTU, Yes! But his Huscarles better be able to enforce it. Then again,
IMTU, an elected official making anti-imperial rules is committing Treason,
since while ruling a world he holds "Honorary Baron" status... IMTU, all
rulers are required to swear fealty to AT LEAST the subsector Duke, and
though him to the Emperor and the Sector Duke. Refusal is Sedition, and
grounds for Imperial Arrest. Then again, I have 3 basic social classes
imperium wide: Noble, Citizen, and Subject... individual worlds may have
more, but the difference between citizen and subject is service in some
imperially approved carreer, in which some imperial service occurs. Minimum
4 years of service.

Appeals go up the chain, fist the subsector duke, then the sector duke,
then the Archduke (if in place), and then the emperor. If in a "Member
polity", their noble is the first appeal. Certain member polities have
appeal directly to their viceroy, and then the emperor, For example, the
Vegan Autonomous District, and a few others.

I allow Citizens and Nobles appeal to the nobles in civil and criminal
trials. In the case of Nobles, the local moot actually hears the appeal,
with the subsector duke as Presiding Judge, and the members as the
appellate-jury. Also, IMTU, Nobles MUST have a trial by Jury, including at
least 1 noble.

