Could be perfectly reasonable (for certain values of reasonable). I
think one recent case involved corporations giving stuff to the Secretary
of Agriculture. The corps were convicted (pled guilty even?) while the
(now former) SecAg was acquitted. 
> 
> Well, I don\'t know if this can happen in the USA or anywhere else,
> but there was a murder here in Norway, were in the criminal case, the
> kid (who was charged of killing his cousine) was found not quilty, while
> when the killed girls parents brought him up on civil charges, they
> were awarded several hundred thousand Norwegian kroner. 
> 
> Not guilty, son, but you still have to pay.

Criminal vs. civil action. cf O.J. Simpson. 

In the US, obtaining a criminal conviction (where you may go to jail
and/or have certain right stripped) requires a higher degree of proof
than a civil judgement (where you simply have money/property taken
away or other actions compelled). It can appear maddeningly nonsensical,
but the criminal acquittal often is a result of the state being
sloppy in its case (cf O.J. Simpson). 
> 
> 
> ObTrav: A planet with several types of courts might have you aqquited
>         in one, but when the charges are brought before another, with 
>         no relations to the first, you pay. Only the lawyers of the
>         world would know which court would be the best for your case. 
