    'body' => 'From reading the latest Scientific American, I got an unexpected
"bonus". They had an article about the balloon that set the record by
floating non-stop around the world. 

A point I hadn\'t considered was that these balloons fly well above
breathable air and are thus actually *sealed* environments ars far as
air and water are concerned (possible wastes also). 

From the diagram of the capsule, it\'s pretty obvious that you can get
the life support consumables for 2-3 people for at least 3 weeks into a
space the size of a small closet! (The flight took 19 days, and \'d have
to assume they had some reserves).

Once I get my web browser running again I may have to go digging for
details about the life support arrangements. 

But in essence, all those big tanks outside were propane tanks for the
burner. The cabin had  lithium hydroxide canisters to remove CO2, a
tank of LOX to replace oxygen that was used, and a tank of LN2 to
replace nitrogen in the event of a major loss of pressure. 

I assume heating used the propane, burned with external air. No mention
was made of what they did about excess humidity, though given the
typical outside temps they could easily have *frozen* or at least
condensed it out and then dealt with it via the waste disposal system
(whatever that may have been). 

In any case, this looks like another data point pointing towards *low*
life support costs for air and probably water. 

Since I have *no* firm date for when I get the system that can do web
browsing up again, I\'d be grateful if someone else decided to track
this down and post the info to the list. 

