    'topic' => ' GT Starship gearheadedness',
    'body' => '>Date: Thu, 4 Nov 1999 14:39:48 -0600
>From: "Joseph R. Dietrich" <yikes@evansville.net>
>Subject: GT Starship gearheadedness (kinda long)
>
>1) Nuclear Dampers. I can\'t, for the life of me, find what a nuclear damper
>is supposed to do in the starship combat system. The CA-15 has an Optimized
>Damper, so I assume that\'s one module with 10-mile coverage. But what does
>that translate to in the combat system?

VE2 nuclear dampers prevent nuclear explosions (but not power generation)
within their radius of effect. Since the damage done by a nuclear-tipped
missile is a function of range to the target at detonation, this
effectively limits the amount of damage.

It\'s not clear to me, however, that this is a good model of how nuclear
dampers work in Traveller. Traveller nuclear dampers are point-effect, not
area-effect, weapons that have to be targetted on each individual missile.

>2) Spinal mounts. Oh, those spinal mounts. The CA-15 has a NPAW model T,
>which is roughly twice the size of the NPAW listed in the book (3,000 spaces
>v. 1500 or so), so I\'m going to have to build one. I started by trying to
>reverse-engineer the NPAWs in the book, but found that I couldn\'t get the
>numbers to match! Oh, I get the stats all right, but I can\'t seem to make it
>fit in the mass and space alotted. I come up with:
>
>   Weapon: 11853 tons mass, 2370 spaces (948 if you use cf/50
>      for volume instead of cf/20 as per GUPRS Vehicles, pg. 42)
>   Full Stablization: 115 tons mass, 237 spaces (95)
>   Power Plant: 1898 tons mass, 152 spaces
>   Energy Bank: 32 tons mass, 1 space
>
>For a total of: 13898 tons mass, 2760 spaces (1196).

You forgot long term access space for the power plant, I think: 304 spaces
+ 1196 = 1,500. Did you also figure using long tons (2,240 lbs) rather than
short tons (2,000 lbs)? That might account for the apparent weight difference.

>As far as I can tell, it requires no crew stations -- as a hull weapon, it\'s
>fired from the bridge by the chief gunner or pilot (as per GT pg. 150). What
>am I missing here?

My plan is to reinstate the crew requirement from HG: 1 crewman per 100
dtons of weapons. These are mostly technicians. Since the spinal mount is
fired by pointing the entire ship, it falls to the Chief Pilot to aim it.
There may or may not be a separate Gunnery Officer pulling the trigger.

>3) Armor. Why is total surface area the area of the hull plus the *total*
>area of all the ships turrets and bays? I would think that, since the
>turrets and bays are at least partially imbedded in the hull, they wouldn\'t
>count as surface area. Bays especially, since they are now almost completely
>*inside* the hull.

The surface area of turrets and bays is calculated for just that portion
which is outside the hull proper. It is in addition to the hull armor
primarily because that\'s the way VE2 handles turret superstructures; it
also avoids arguments about whether the hull is more vulnerable under the
turret (it\'s not). Bays in GT2/e went back to being Honking Big Turrets.
GT: Starships will present both versions (internal and external bays) as
options. Internal bays will not require separate armoring.
