>
> Correct, to a point.  Although each person varies in his or her capacities,
> even beginning to attempt such a determination may be beyond most 3I era
> Muslims.  You are correct that one\'s intention is the most pertinent aspect
> of any action ~ not necessarily just the intent to face the appropriate
> direction when beginning prayer, but the intention to please Allah by
> keeping the prayers in the first place.  Each believer would likely rise to
> his or her own level of accuracy, just as they do now.

And I\'m sure that as (I am told) many mosques have a plaque or other
indicator indicating the direction of of Mecca now, offworld mosques
might well have some sort of indicator controlled by a computer. 

For personal use, something incorporating a gps type system might work.

I do agree that the direction would too little to worry about when
taking even a jump 6 in the Marches. I was being a bit disingenious
with regard to prayers in jump, knowing that some scholars will nitpick
doctrines to death, and it might be argued that one couldn\'t know the
right direction while in jump.

As a practical matter, it should be possible to ask the Astrogator
which way Earth is, and ask the captain to orient the ship in such a
manner that one can easily pray in the right direction (ie so that the
"proper direction" is towards the ceiling or the like.

>> I would expect that recycled water would not be considered kosher,
>
> I might have to disagree, but neither would I consider myself of an
> extremely strict orthodoxy.  Once anything has been rendered into its
> components elements and remade into a new form, I would posit that most
> "modern" Muslims would accept it as halal; I would.  If not, then one should
> not drink from a well, or even be able to eat anything that hadn\'t been
> touched in even some remote fashion by things haram.  There are things in
> the water table that make me shudder to think... and I don\'t mean just the
> fluoride.  I can\'t speak for Judaism, though.

I expect that it\'d depend on just how Orthodox the Jew in question was.
And on what sort of ruling Orthodox rabbis make on the subject.

>> As to how one determines the Islamic calendar dates while outside the
>> Solar system, I would expect that, within sight of Sol and her planets
>> (in M:1100, that could be quite some distance), direct observation of
>> Sol, Terra, and Luna, plus calculation of light\'s travel time from Sol
>> to the point of observation, would fulfill the requirement for "direct
>> observation" of the new moon.
>
> I would suspect that 3I Muslims would have to follow their own local lunar
> calendar for most things other than keeping track of comparable dates to
> discuss intelligently with others.  There is much discord amongst the Ummah
> about "which moon" to follow even today for determining events, such as Eid.
> There are hadith, IMO, that rule on the subject which state clearly that one
> should follow the sightings of the moon in one\'s own city or region, *not*
> the sightings of the moon elsewhere.  I suppose it would be an interesting
> debate, though, would it not?
>
> This, of course, becomes difficult on a moonless sphere, just as prayer time
> calculation becomes very burdensome close to the poles of Terra.  I\'ve
> pondered it myself, but have sought no scholar\'s futwa on the topic yet.  :)
