> now-common, though in-authentic, practice of following the sightings of the
> moon in Mecca or Medina might gain even wider acceptance, although
> time/distance will make even that more nigh impossible.

Think there\'s a chance that for those places, they\'d go by the
calculated time of the new moon?

BTW, our moon is likely to be very unusual. Consider the situation on
Mars. There are two moons, and you get "new moon" once a *day* for one
of them. And as I recall the other will be "new" at least 2-3 times a
week. 

Then there\'s the places like Regina, which *are* Moons. At least if you
lived on the "inner" hemisphere, "new moon" would be easy to determine.
It\'d occur as the shadow of your moon crossed the center line of the
gas giant you were orbiting. Alas, it\'d occur about once a (standard)
week, and would always be at *midnight* local time. 

>> Besides, at least some Islamic rules (such as daytime fasting during
>> Ramadan) are relaxed for those who are traveling, especially when
>> travelling in service to the Islamic faith.
>
> Traveling is a relative thing...  If you live aboard a starship for most (or
> all) of your life, are you still traveling?  I don\'t think so, but we all
