    'from' => 'gridlore@pop.mindspring.com',
    'body' => 'At 05:56 AM 11/5/1999 PST, you wrote:

>Actually, that\'s more due to TL differences. With the tech the Iraqis
>had, they *were* camoflauged and/or "behind cover".
>
>Imagine their shock when it became clear that as far as *our* gear was
>concerned, they had neither. 

The Iraqis proved to be very clever.  They would haul wrecked tanks into
fighting positions, and light fires in the engine compartments, while
driving a working tank into the posotion previously occupied by the junked
vehicle.  When the Coalition planes came back, they\'d hit the same wreck
over an over again.

Inside Iraq, airfield personel became very adept at painting craters on
runways, to convince USAF photo recon specialists that the runway way
indeed out of service.

An Iraqi armor commander, captured on the second day of the war, put it best:

"I entered Kuwait with 48 T-72s.  After a month of air attacks, I had 45.
After an hour of combat with the M1, I had none."
