    'body' => 'From: Black ICE <wombat@premier.net>

> ObTrav:  Try this for a deeply unpleasant sentence:  A day before a
> convicted felon has finished serving his/her/its time in prison, put
> said convict into cold sleep for a century or two.  Then thaw the
> convict out, have him/her/it serve the last day of the sentence, and
> then be released.  Temporal exile....

Now to turn this into an adventure idea:

PCs come across a STL generation vessel, with several thousand 
members of some minor race held in Cold Sleep.  Probably no info 
available to translate the linguistics of the computer records, and 
everything on board indicates that this is a colony ship of some form 
or another.

If PCs initiate the automated unthawing processes, about a thousand
people are released, and start rampaging.  Further investigating
may reveal that these are convicts who are being sent to found a
penal colony due to inhumane acts of an incredibly vile nature (at
least according to their culture, anyway,) and their homeworld has
forced them into this exile as punishment.

The PCs are horribly outnumbered by a bunch of TL 8 goons, and may
possibly be taken by surprise.  If they can get away, (after a very
exciting escape sequence,) notifying the Imperial authorities should
take care of the colony ship drifting between the stars.  But if the
leader of the convicts can manage to keep the PCs alive, then there\'s
the trip back to the cons\' homeworld, where the leader hopes to exact 
vengeance against those who did this to him, and the PCs have the 
only ship capable of FTL transit that he has access to.  :)

Just a thought,
Jason

