    'month' => '11',
    'index' => 'ed307',
    'body' => 'Same happened to OJ Simpson. It happens regularly in the US. Shouldn\'t be
allowed (They should really be combined, to to double jeopardy), but they
aren\'t. And in the US, civil cases are generally by "preponderance of the
evidence" versus "beyond a reasonable doubt". There was apparently
reasonable doubt in the criminal trial, but the civil trial found it to be
"more likely than not" that he killed his ex.
>>>>>>>>>>>>>>

Then there was the Rodney King beating case a few years back - some
Los Angeles, California police officers got a bit too enthusiastic in their
apprehending of one Rodney King, who was resisting arrest...and 
someone got it on videotape.

The officers were acquitted of using excessive force- apparently it wasn\'t 
clear to the jury just how much Mr. King was actually resisting, and 
they could not get to the beyond reasonable doubt stage. Mr. King
proceeded to sue, of course (taking the officers to civil court), as
expected. What I did not expect was for the United States Federal 
Government to charge the officers with violating Mr. King\'s civil rights. It 
looked like the government had decided that this high-profile, emotionally
charged circus of a case needed a guilty verdict for spin purposes,
and tried to create a guilty verdict themselves when the courts in 
California did not do so.

ObTrav: Legal skill may run a poor second to a high Social Standing
score, or other evidence of good governmental connections.

Walt Smith
