    'body' => '>It\'s not clear to me, however, that this is a good model of how nuclear
>dampers work in Traveller. Traveller nuclear dampers are point-effect, not
>area-effect, weapons that have to be targetted on each individual missile.

I was always under the impression they were field-effect screens, at least
until TNE. MegaTraveller (which I cut my teeth on) seemed to treat them as
such -- no ND turrets, just screen packages.

>You forgot long term access space for the power plant, I think: 304 spaces
>+ 1196 = 1,500. Did you also figure using long tons (2,240 lbs) rather than
>short tons (2,000 lbs)? That might account for the apparent weight difference.

Short tons are what I used. Is this correct or incorrect? Question: Why do
spinal mounts use cf/50 for volume, when they would seem to be completely
enclosed in the hull (after all, the ship is built around it) and thus
subject to the cf/20 requirement?

>The surface area of turrets and bays is calculated for just that portion
>which is outside the hull proper.

Except that a turret is 3 spaces, right? Plus 1 in the hull for crewstation
and turning mechanism? The surface area of 800 would seem to suggest that
the turret is armored in it\'s entirety, as if it were completely
free-standing cube seperate from the hull (1,500 cf = 800 sf surface area,
according to GV). The 50-space bays are the same.

>My plan is to reinstate the crew requirement from HG: 1 crewman per 100
>dtons of weapons. These are mostly technicians.

I ended up doing this for the Type T NPAWS I designed -- 30 crew stations.
I actually came pretty close to the canonical size 3,001 spaces, with a
damage of 6d x 16,700. I\'ll post the cruiser once I get it finished tonight
or this weekend.

Another question: What are good ballpark figures for warship armor? The
Type T spinal mount is the largest NPAWs available to the Imperium
historically, and as I have it figured its maximum possible damage is
601,200 (and averaging around 350,700). The CA-15 has an armor value of 80
(1080 cm hard steel) in MT, which is roughly DR 29,760. The Type T\'s going
to go right through that, but it\'ll still take several hits to kill the
ship (it\'s got lots of hitpoints). OTOH, according to FSotSI, a BB-15, with
an armor value of 120 is going to have a DR of somthing like 6,000,000,
which seems unreasonable by an order of magnitude, at least.

Whaaa! I want that G:Starships book to come out *now*. ;-)

Ciao,

Joseph R. Dietrich
